#. type: Yaml Front Matter Hash Value: title
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "The mathematics of guided laplacians and harmonic transposition"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:25
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This article presents the mathematics of Ansel's highlight reconstruction : the original 2021\n"
"`guided laplacians` design, whose general ideas had only ever been sketched on the *pixls.us*\n"
"forum,[^forum] and **harmonic transposition**, the method that replaced it after a ground-truth\n"
"study exposed a magnitude-recovery bug.[^impl] It is organized so each reader finds their\n"
"section : the [results](#results) and each method's *Intuition & background* need no\n"
"mathematics ; developers will find the *Implementation & optimizations* subsections and the\n"
"[performance](#performance) study ; the\n"
"[theoretical findings](#theoretical-findings) and the\n"
"[graveyard annex](#annex--the-graveyard) are written to be\n"
"reusable outside photography ; and\n"
"[how this work was actually done](#how-this-work-was-actually-done) documents the man–machine\n"
"research protocol behind it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:44
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"When a camera sensor saturates, the three colour channels do not clip at the same time, so a blown\n"
"highlight drifts in colour, usually toward magenta. This article documents Ansel's highlight\n"
"reconstruction end to end and in the order it happened : the original 2021 **guided laplacians**\n"
"(wavelet-detail transfer through a guided filter, never fully written down before), the\n"
"ground-truth study that exposed its magnitude bug, and the method that replaced it — **harmonic\n"
"transposition**, which keeps the guided filter's local colour-line model but carries its\n"
"*coefficients* across the blown zone as smooth diffused fields steered by the surviving\n"
"channels' structure, debiases the sensor's\n"
"saturation rolloff before fitting, and hands each frequency band and pixel class to the estimator\n"
"that is measurably best there. Every design decision is backed by a number on a public bench, and\n"
"the failures are documented with the same care as the successes, including two results we believe\n"
"are general : seam energy at any estimator hand-off equals the estimators' disagreement and cannot\n"
"be weighted away, and the validity of a colour-line deep inside a blown zone is undecidable from\n"
"the data around it.[^he][^qin]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:45
#: content/resources/color-management-linux.md:24
#, no-wrap
msgid "The problem"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:47
#, no-wrap
msgid "The magenta cast"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:54
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"A digital sensor is an array of photosites, each covered by one coloured filter of a **colour filter\n"
"array** (CFA) : the Bayer pattern (2×2 of R, G, G, B) or Fuji's X-Trans (6×6). Each photosite is a\n"
"potential well that fills with photo-electrons during the exposure and saturates at a fixed\n"
"capacity. Because the well capacity is a property of the silicon, **all three colours saturate at\n"
"roughly the same raw code value**.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:60
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The trap is white balance. A neutral grey subject does not produce equal raw signals in the three\n"
"channels: the CFA transmissions, the sensor's spectral sensitivity, and the scene illuminant all\n"
"differ per channel. To render such a subject as neutral, the raw developer multiplies each channel\n"
"by a **white-balance coefficient** : typically the green channel is left near $1$ while red and\n"
"blue are multiplied up by $1.5$ to $2$.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:72
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now follow a neutral highlight as it gets brighter. At the sensor there is nothing per-channel\n"
"about saturation: the three raw signals climb toward **one shared ceiling — the full well** — and\n"
"clip at more or less the same value. The magenta is manufactured *afterwards*, by the\n"
"white-balance gains: multiplying each channel changes both its slope on the way up **and** the\n"
"level its clipped plateau lands on. Green (gain $\\approx 1$) plateaus where the sensor left it ;\n"
"blue and red are pushed up by their gains and plateau **above** it. Past saturation the recorded\n"
"ratios are no longer neutral — red and blue overshoot green, and the \"white\" highlight reads as\n"
"**magenta**. (On real subjects the channels do still clip in *sequence* — the subject's own colour\n"
"and the per-channel sensitivities stagger the onsets, which is why partially-clipped pixels exist\n"
"and carry surviving guides — but the magenta of a blown neutral is the work of the gains, not of\n"
"per-channel thresholds.)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:74
#, no-wrap
msgid "{{< plotly title=\"Left : at the sensor, a neutral highlight drives all three channels toward the same ceiling — the full well — and they clip together. Right : the white-balance gains (here R × 2.0, B × 1.5, G × 1.0) change both the slope and the height of each clipped plateau ; red and blue land above green, and the recorded color drifts to magenta — even though the subject is grey and the sensor clipped all channels at the same level.\" src=\"magenta-clipping.json\" caption=\"true\" >}}\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:82
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"{{< note >}}\n"
"This is a purely mechanical, colorimetric artifact of the capture apparatus. There is no magenta in\n"
"the scene. Any reconstruction that works in a colour space *after* demosaicing is already fighting a\n"
"hue error that a demosaicing algorithm will have smeared across neighbouring pixels. Reconstructing\n"
"*before* demosaicing, while the data is still a clean per-channel mosaic, is the whole point of the\n"
"guided-laplacian method.\n"
"{{< /note >}}\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:85
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The value at which a channel is declared clipped is not the numeric maximum but a per-channel\n"
"threshold derived from the raw white point:\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:86
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\text{clip}_c = 0.995 \\times \\texttt{clip} \\times \\text{white}_c,\n"
msgstr "\\text{clip}_c = 0.995 \\times \\texttt{clip} \\times \\text{white}_c,\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:94
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"where $\\text{white}_c$ is the module's `processed_maximum` for channel $c$ (the per-channel raw\n"
"white level surviving the earlier pipeline stages) and `clip` is a user safety factor around $1$.\n"
"The $0.995$ margin keeps almost-saturated photosites (whose response has already gone nonlinear\n"
"near the top of the well) out of the \"valid\" set.[^impl]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:95
#, no-wrap
msgid "Simpler fixes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:99
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Ansel's module offers three cheaper reconstruction modes before the guided-laplacian one, and they\n"
"are worth stating because they frame what the expensive method buys:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:109
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"* **Clip** simply crushes every channel to the common threshold $\\texttt{clip}\\times\\min_c \\text{white}_c$\n"
"  (the same white levels, without the $0.995$ margin). No magenta,\n"
"  but every clipped region becomes a flat, textureless white blob.\n"
"* **Reconstruct in LCh** converts each Bayer block to a luminance/chroma/hue triple, rescales the\n"
"  chroma of clipped blocks to match the unclipped luminance, and converts back. It removes the hue\n"
"  drift but cannot invent texture.[^impl]\n"
"* **Reconstruct color (inpaint)** propagates colour *ratios* from neighbouring unclipped pixels along\n"
"  rows and columns, using the exponential-decay ratio update of Magic Lantern's algorithm. It is\n"
"  fast and directional but one-dimensional and easily fooled by complex edges.[^impl]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:112
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The `guided laplacians` mode is the only one that restores both the **texture and the magnitude** of\n"
"a clipped region, by borrowing from the channels that did survive along the local colour-line.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:118
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Upstream Darktable ships two reconstruction modes that Ansel does not carry, and they make an\n"
"instructive comparison because they start from a *different assumption* about what a blown\n"
"highlight is. Both were developed by the G'mic and Darktable teams and both work, like our method, on the raw mosaic : each colour channel is first\n"
"approximated everywhere from its 3×3 photosite neighbourhood, giving a crude but full-resolution\n"
"per-channel image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:127
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**Inpaint opposed** rests on one empirical observation : for a clipped channel, the mean of the\n"
"two *other* channels (the \"opposed\" average, computed in cube-root space to compress the\n"
"dynamic range) is a good estimate of the missing value in the vast majority of images. The\n"
"mechanism is accordingly simple : replace every clipped value by that opposed average, then add\n"
"one **global** chrominance offset, measured on the pixels morphologically closest to the clipped\n"
"areas, to absorb the overall colour cast. Its documented failure modes are the scenes where one fixed\n"
"relationship cannot hold : mixed lighting, white balance far from the pipeline's assumption, or\n"
"several light sources with different colours feeding different highlights.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:140
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**Segmentation based** refines the same base estimator with spatial adaptation. Each channel's\n"
"clipped pixels are flood-filled into connected *segments* (optionally merged by a morphological\n"
"closing, the \"combine\" control) ; for each segment, the algorithm searches its unclipped border\n"
"for the best **candidate** pixel (scored by local standard deviation and median in a 5×5\n"
"window) and transplants that candidate's pseudo-chrominance (the channel minus the opposed\n"
"mean, again in cube-root space) across the whole segment. If no convincing candidate exists, it\n"
"falls back to a segment-wide average with a chrominance correction. Where *all* channels clip,\n"
"a separate \"rebuild\" pass extrapolates a luminance surface from the border gradients, gated by a\n"
"distance transform — the closest cousin, in this whole landscape, of our biharmonic dome. The\n"
"assumptions are thus : one representative chrominance *per segment* (better than one per image,\n"
"but still flat within a segment), texture inherited from whatever the surviving channels carry,\n"
"and gradient extrapolation where nothing survived.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:142
#, no-wrap
msgid "Both are desperate attempt at filling the damaged area with _something_ plausible, but promote flat colored surfaces at the wrong magnitude.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:143
#, no-wrap
msgid "First principles"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:149
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The method is an assembly of four ideas. Two of them (discrete Laplacians and the à-trous\n"
"B-spline pyramid) are shared verbatim with [*diffuse or sharpen*](/resources/diffuse-or-sharpen-math/) and\n"
"are only summarized here. The other two, the guided filter and chrominance diffusion, carry the\n"
"reconstruction and are derived in full.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:150
#, no-wrap
msgid "Gradients and Laplacians"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:153
#, no-wrap
msgid "For a discrete image $u(i,j)$, the **gradient** measures the local slope,\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:154
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\nabla u = \\left( \\frac{u(i+1,j) - u(i-1,j)}{2}, \\; \\frac{u(i,j+1) - u(i,j-1)}{2} \\right),\n"
msgstr "\\nabla u = \\left( \\frac{u(i+1,j) - u(i-1,j)}{2}, \\; \\frac{u(i,j+1) - u(i,j-1)}{2} \\right),\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:160
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"and the **Laplacian** measures the local curvature : how much a pixel departs from the average of\n"
"its neighbours,\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:161
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\Delta u = \\frac{\\partial^2 u}{\\partial x^2} + \\frac{\\partial^2 u}{\\partial y^2}.\n"
msgstr "\\Delta u = \\frac{\\partial^2 u}{\\partial x^2} + \\frac{\\partial^2 u}{\\partial y^2}.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:172
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The Laplacian is the workhorse here because it isolates *texture* as oscillation around a local\n"
"average (it is zero on flat regions and responds only to local contrast) and because it is\n"
"**linear**: over- or under-exposing the image simply rescales it (a property we lean on below).\n"
"Isolating texture this way is what lets us transplant it between channels without dragging along the\n"
"guide's absolute brightness; the difference in overall magnitude between a clipped channel and its\n"
"guide is absorbed by the guided filter's slope, not by the Laplacian itself. Ansel uses the\n"
"rotationally-symmetric 9-point stencil from Oono & Puri\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:173
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\\mathbf{K}_{\\text{iso}} =\n"
"\\begin{bmatrix}\n"
"\\tfrac14 & \\tfrac12 & \\tfrac14 \\\\\n"
"\\tfrac12 & -3       & \\tfrac12 \\\\\n"
"\\tfrac14 & \\tfrac12 & \\tfrac14\n"
"\\end{bmatrix},\n"
msgstr ""
"\\mathbf{K}_{\\text{iso}} =\n"
"\\begin{bmatrix}\n"
"\\tfrac14 & \\tfrac12 & \\tfrac14 \\\\\n"
"\\tfrac12 & -3       & \\tfrac12 \\\\\n"
"\\tfrac14 & \\tfrac12 & \\tfrac14\n"
"\\end{bmatrix},\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:184
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"whose angular error is much smaller than the naive 5-point cross, so diffusion does not privilege\n"
"the pixel-grid axes.[^oono][^patra][^ripl]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:189
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To act on structures of many sizes, the image is split into frequency bands by repeatedly blurring\n"
"it with the separable cardinal B-spline kernel\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:190
#, no-wrap
msgid "h_0 = \\frac{1}{16}[1,4,6,4,1],\n"
msgstr "h_0 = \\frac{1}{16}[1,4,6,4,1],\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:198
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"a compact approximation of a Gaussian of parameter $\\sigma_B \\approx 1.0554$.[^unser] At scale $s$\n"
"the taps are spread apart by a stride of $2^s$ pixels (\"à-trous\" = \"with holes\"), so the same tiny\n"
"kernel reaches ever farther without ever growing in cost. Writing $G_s$ for the successive\n"
"low-pass (progressively blurred) images and $H_s$ for the **detail bands**,\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:199
#, no-wrap
msgid "G_{-1} = u, \\qquad G_s = h_{2^s} * G_{s-1}, \\qquad H_s = G_{s-1} - G_s,\n"
msgstr "G_{-1} = u, \\qquad G_s = h_{2^s} * G_{s-1}, \\qquad H_s = G_{s-1} - G_s,\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:207
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"the image is exactly the sum of its bands, $u = \\sum_{s=0}^{n-1} H_s + G_{n-1}$. A detail band $H_s$ is a\n"
"difference of Gaussians, which is itself a scaled approximation of a Laplacian-of-Gaussian — so\n"
"\"filtering the band $H_s$\" and \"applying a Laplacian at scale $s$\" are two views of the same\n"
"operation. The full derivation, including how the equivalent Gaussian radius grows as\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:208
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\sigma_{G,s} = \\sigma_B \\sqrt{\\frac{4^{s+1}-1}{3}},\n"
msgstr "\\sigma_{G,s} = \\sigma_B \\sqrt{\\frac{4^{s+1}-1}{3}},\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:213
#, no-wrap
msgid "is given in the [companion article on *diffuse or sharpen*](/resources/diffuse-or-sharpen-math/#the-à-trous-b-spline-pyramid).[^impl][^dreggn]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:221
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"{{< note >}}\n"
"Two products of this pyramid are used below. The **low-pass** $G_s$ is a local weighted mean at\n"
"scale $s$ — exactly the local average the guided filter needs, at a whole ladder of window sizes.\n"
"The **detail band** $H_s$ is a scaled Laplacian, the operator the chrominance-diffusion fallback\n"
"integrates. The reconstruction proper works on the $G_s$ (which carry the colour's magnitude); the\n"
"fallback works on the $H_s$.\n"
"{{< /note >}}\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:222
#, no-wrap
msgid "The guided filter"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:228
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The **guided filter** of He, Sun and Tang is the engine that borrows texture from a good channel\n"
"into a clipped one.[^he] Suppose we want to produce an output image $q$ that stays faithful to some\n"
"target $p$ but wears the *edges and texture* of a **guide** $I$. Assume that, inside any small\n"
"window $\\omega_k$ around pixel $k$, the output is an **affine function of the guide**:\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:229
#, no-wrap
msgid "q_i = a_k \\, I_i + b_k, \\qquad \\forall i \\in \\omega_k.\n"
msgstr "q_i = a_k \\, I_i + b_k, \\qquad \\forall i \\in \\omega_k.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:239
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This single assumption, a *local colour line*, is the whole model. It says that within a small\n"
"patch the channel we are rebuilding is just a scaled, shifted copy of the guide. It is the same\n"
"prior that underlies cross-channel demosaicing, dehazing, image matting and colorization: natural\n"
"surfaces trace *colour lines* (locally, their channels are affinely related) because most edges are\n"
"changes in *reflectance* that scale all channels together.[^colorline] Under an affine map,\n"
"$\\nabla q = a_k \\nabla I$, so $q$ inherits every edge of $I$, merely rescaled by $a_k$.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:242
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"We fit $(a_k, b_k)$ by least squares, keeping $a_k$ small to avoid amplifying noise (a ridge term\n"
"$\\varepsilon a_k^2$):\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:243
#, no-wrap
msgid "E(a_k, b_k) = \\sum_{i \\in \\omega_k} \\Big[ (a_k I_i + b_k - p_i)^2 + \\varepsilon \\, a_k^2 \\Big].\n"
msgstr "E(a_k, b_k) = \\sum_{i \\in \\omega_k} \\Big[ (a_k I_i + b_k - p_i)^2 + \\varepsilon \\, a_k^2 \\Big].\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:248
#, no-wrap
msgid "Setting the derivatives to zero gives the closed form that appears, almost verbatim, in the code:\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:249
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\\begin{aligned}\n"
"a_k &= \\frac{\\operatorname{cov}_{\\omega_k}(I, p)}{\\operatorname{var}_{\\omega_k}(I) + \\varepsilon}, \\\\\n"
"b_k &= \\bar{p}_{\\omega_k} - a_k \\, \\bar{I}_{\\omega_k}.\n"
"\\end{aligned}\n"
msgstr ""
"\\begin{aligned}\n"
"a_k &= \\frac{\\operatorname{cov}_{\\omega_k}(I, p)}{\\operatorname{var}_{\\omega_k}(I) + \\varepsilon}, \\\\\n"
"b_k &= \\bar{p}_{\\omega_k} - a_k \\, \\bar{I}_{\\omega_k}.\n"
"\\end{aligned}\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:261
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The covariance in the numerator (a measure of how much guide and target rise and fall together)\n"
"is the key: where they move together, $a_k \\to 1$ and\n"
"the guide's texture is copied through; where the guide is flat ($\\operatorname{var} \\to 0$), $a_k\n"
"\\to 0$ and the output falls back to the local mean $\\bar p$. The ridge parameter $\\varepsilon$ sets\n"
"the scale below which variations are treated as noise and smoothed rather than transferred.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:265
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"{{< note >}}\n"
"He's guided filter has a second step (averaging the per-window coefficients $(a_k, b_k)$ over all windows covering a pixel) that keeps the output from looking blocky. The rebuilt implementation gets the same smoothing for free by computing the window statistics with a smooth kernel (a Gaussian) rather than a hard box : overlapping smooth windows make $a$ and $b$ smoothly varying fields, so $a,I + b$ is already artifact-free without a separate averaging pass. This is not a cosmetic detail : replaying the same fit with a hard box window of comparable support leaves visible axis-aligned streaks and stepped plateaus wherever image structure crosses a window boundary, and costs about a third more error on the bench's edge scene. The 2021 code, for its part, used a hard $3\\times3$ box with no averaging at all — it got away with it because the window is three pixels wide and the iterated diffusion smooths whatever it leaves behind.[^impl]\n"
"{{< /note >}}\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:266
#, no-wrap
msgid "Diffusion as color inpainting"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:273
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Filling the *colour* of a hole is a different problem from filling its *texture*. A hole's colour\n"
"should vary **smoothly** and match its rim; it should not carry high-frequency detail (fine,\n"
"rapidly-varying texture) of its own. The natural formalism is the **Dirichlet energy**, the\n"
"total amount of variation the image contains, large where it wiggles and zero where it is\n"
"constant :\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:274
#, no-wrap
msgid "E[u] = \\int_\\Omega \\lVert \\nabla u \\rVert^2 \\, \\mathrm{d}x,\n"
msgstr "E[u] = \\int_\\Omega \\lVert \\nabla u \\rVert^2 \\, \\mathrm{d}x,\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:280
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"whose minimizer over the hole $\\Omega$, with the surrounding pixels as boundary condition, is the\n"
"**harmonic** function satisfying $\\Delta u = 0$.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:287
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"(Notation, used throughout the article : $\\lVert v \\rVert$ is the **euclidean norm** of a\n"
"vector — for the gradient, $\\lVert \\nabla u \\rVert = \\sqrt{(\\partial_x u)^2 + (\\partial_y u)^2}$,\n"
"the local slope magnitude ; $\\lvert s \\rvert$ is the absolute value of a scalar ; and\n"
"$\\langle \\cdot \\rangle$ — angle brackets — is the **average of the enclosed quantity over the\n"
"region's pixels**.) The gradient descent of this energy is precisely\n"
"the **heat equation**\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:288
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial t} = \\Delta u,\n"
msgstr "\\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial t} = \\Delta u,\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:298
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"i.e. isotropic diffusion, *isotropic* meaning direction-blind, spreading equally in all\n"
"directions. Running it spreads the boundary colour inward until the hole is filled by\n"
"a smooth, curvature-free surface. This is the same anisotropic-heat-transfer inpainting model of\n"
"Qin et al. that Ansel already uses for *diffuse or sharpen*, restricted here to its isotropic\n"
"case.[^qin] We will apply it not to the pixels but to the **colour ratios**, so that only chrominance is\n"
"smoothed while the reconstructed luminance is left alone.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:301
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**Steering the diffusion : the anisotropic extension.** The Dirichlet energy above treats every\n"
"direction equally ; it is *isotropic*. It generalizes to a weighted form,\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:302
#, no-wrap
msgid "E(u) = \\int_\\Omega \\nabla u^\\top D \\,\\nabla u ,\n"
msgstr "E(u) = \\int_\\Omega \\nabla u^\\top D \\,\\nabla u ,\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:314
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"where the **diffusion tensor** $D$ is a small symmetric matrix defined at every pixel whose job\n"
"is to re-weight directions : full conductance along one of its eigenvectors, damped conductance\n"
"along the other. Minimizing this energy solves $\\mathrm{div}(D\\\\,\\nabla u) = 0$ (its\n"
"Euler–Lagrange equation), and with $D$ the identity everywhere it reduces exactly to the\n"
"isotropic case above. The point of the machinery is *steering* : choose the strong direction\n"
"along the image's **isophotes** (the lines of constant brightness) and the damped one across\n"
"them, and the diffusion smooths a quantity *along* image structure while refusing to carry it\n"
"*across* edges.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:319
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Discretizing this safely takes one precaution. Writing the tensor\n"
"$D = \\begin{pmatrix} a & b \\\\ b & c \\end{pmatrix}$ (averaged between each pixel and its\n"
"neighbour, with the cross term clamped to $|b| \\leq \\min(a, c)$), the divergence\n"
"$\\operatorname{div}(D\\\\,\\nabla u)$ becomes a sum over the eight neighbours with weights\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:320
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"w_{\\pm e_x} = a - |b|, \\qquad w_{\\pm e_y} = c - |b|, \\qquad\n"
"w_{\\pm(e_x + e_y)} = \\max(b,\\, 0), \\qquad w_{\\pm(e_x - e_y)} = \\max(-b,\\, 0),\n"
msgstr ""
"w_{\\pm e_x} = a - |b|, \\qquad w_{\\pm e_y} = c - |b|, \\qquad\n"
"w_{\\pm(e_x + e_y)} = \\max(b,\\, 0), \\qquad w_{\\pm(e_x - e_y)} = \\max(-b,\\, 0),\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:335
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"the nonnegativity-preserving stencil of Weickert : the clamp guarantees **every weight is\n"
"nonnegative**, so the anchored relaxation $u_0 \\leftarrow \\sum_k w_k u_k / \\sum_k w_k$\n"
"replaces each unknown by a *convex combination* of its neighbours. That is the discrete\n"
"maximum principle — the solved values can never leave the range of the anchors, no matter how\n"
"hard the tensor steers — and it is what makes anisotropic diffusion safe to run on data that\n"
"must stay physical. The shipped method uses this machinery in two places : the **transport of\n"
"the colour-line coefficients** across the blown zone (step 3 of the algorithm, where the\n"
"tensor additionally blends between isophote and gradient steering by a measured edge\n"
"probability), and the **chrominance of fully clipped cores** (step 8), where colours must\n"
"follow the recovered luminance's structure and never bleed across it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:336
#, no-wrap
msgid "Biharmonic inpainting"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:343
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Harmonic inpainting is the right tool for a signal that *should* go flat inside the hole : a smooth\n"
"chrominance. It is the wrong tool for one that was still *rising* when the sensor clipped it: a blown\n"
"highlight's magnitude kept climbing, and filling it flat ($\\Delta u = 0$) leaves a matte disk where a\n"
"bright dome belongs. To carry the surrounding **slope** inward instead of erasing it, penalize the\n"
"signal's *bending* rather than its gradient : minimize the thin-plate (biharmonic) energy\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:344
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"E_{\\text{bihar}}[u] = \\int_\\Omega (\\Delta u)^2 \\, \\mathrm{d}\\Omega\n"
"\\qquad \\Longrightarrow \\qquad\n"
"\\Delta^2 u = 0 \\ \\text{ on } \\Omega, \\quad u\\big|_{\\partial\\Omega} = u_{\\text{valid}} ,\n"
msgstr ""
"E_{\\text{bihar}}[u] = \\int_\\Omega (\\Delta u)^2 \\, \\mathrm{d}\\Omega\n"
"\\qquad \\Longrightarrow \\qquad\n"
"\\Delta^2 u = 0 \\ \\text{ on } \\Omega, \\quad u\\big|_{\\partial\\Omega} = u_{\\text{valid}} ,\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:359
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"whose Euler–Lagrange equation (the condition any minimizer of the energy must satisfy) is the\n"
"**biharmonic** equation $\\Delta^2 u = 0$. Where the harmonic\n"
"solution forces $\\Delta u = 0$ (a flat minimal surface), the biharmonic solution makes $\\Delta u$\n"
"*itself* harmonic : the curvature at the rim is carried into the interior, so the boundary's rising\n"
"gradient is extrapolated into a dome (a thin-plate spline). It is the higher-order,\n"
"gradient-*extending* counterpart of diffusion, in the same spirit that *diffuse or sharpen* flips the\n"
"sign of the Laplacian to sharpen rather than smooth. We solve it as a direct sparse linear system on\n"
"the hole, and use it below to rebuild a clipped channel's magnitude from its own valid rim wherever\n"
"no correlated channel survives to guide it.[^ripl]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:360
#, no-wrap
msgid "The 2021 method : guided laplacians"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:369
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Before following the method's evolution, this section documents the original design, as it\n"
"shipped in 2021 and as it still ships today — design unchanged, though it shares one measured\n"
"border-gather fix with the new pipeline (documented with the harmonic refinements below) —\n"
"under the `guided laplacians` mode (the new\n"
"method is a separate, opt-in mode : see the status note further down). It was coded\n"
"against intuition and tuned by eye on natural images, and its general ideas were only ever sketched\n"
"on the pixls.us forum[^forum] ; this is its first complete write-up.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:370
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:652
#, no-wrap
msgid "Intuition & background"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:380
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**The intuition.** Unavoidable clipping happens within light sources : the sun, a flame, a\n"
"specular reflection. Such sources are surrounded by a glowing halo, and that halo carries three\n"
"exploitable kinds of information. First, the colour channels are strongly *correlated* there (they\n"
"all rise toward the source), so a channel that clipped can borrow the shape of a channel that did\n"
"not. Second, the halo's gradients point at the source, so even a fully blown core can be\n"
"plausibly continued by *propagating* the surrounding gradients inward. Third, the halo is coloured like the light source itself, so chrominance can be recovered by propagating RGB ratios inwards. The 2021 design turned each\n"
"intuition into an operator : a **guided transfer** of fine structure between channels, and an\n"
"**iterated diffusion** that pushes structure from the valid surround into the blown region while diffusing colour ratios inwards.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:386
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**The objectives.** Reconstruct *before demosaicing*, on the raw mosaic, so the interpolation\n"
"never sees clipped samples ; never rely on white balance or any assumption about what colour the\n"
"highlight \"should\" be (the light source's own colour is unknowable) ; and prefer smooth, physically\n"
"plausible continuations over sharp hallucinations, because an error in a blown highlight is far\n"
"more visible as a hard artifact than as a soft one.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:394
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**Its record.** On its design cases the method worked, and still does : a sun disc or a specular\n"
"on water is rebuilt with believable structure and without the flat grey patch that plain clipping\n"
"leaves. It preserves gradients where simpler methods (channel ratio scaling, single-colour\n"
"inpainting) flatten them, and since it works on gradients rather than colours it tolerates wrong\n"
"white balance. Two structural limits were understood and accepted from the start : a blown sky\n"
"seen through green leaves is recovered green (the method propagates the *neighbouring* colour, by\n"
"design), and heavy chromatic aberration breaks the channel alignment the colour-line needs.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:395
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:679
#, no-wrap
msgid "The optimization problem"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:404
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**The texture transfer.** The image is decomposed with the [à-trous B-spline\n"
"pyramid](#the-à-trous-b-spline-pyramid) described above : at each scale $s$ the signal splits into\n"
"a low-frequency approximation and a **detail band** $H_s$. Because the cardinal B-spline is very close to a Gaussian, and the detail band is computed scale-wise as the difference with this approximated Gaussian, $H_s$ is itself already close to a Laplacian, rescaled in magnitude (it actually over-evaluates the Laplacian). On each detail band, each clipped\n"
"channel $c$ is fit against a **guide** channel $g$ (chosen per pixel as the channel with the\n"
"strongest local variance, that is, the one carrying the most structure — with no check that the\n"
"guide itself is valid there) with the guided filter derived\n"
"[above](#the-guided-filter) :\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:405
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"H_c \\;\\leftarrow\\; a_c\\, H_g + b_c, \\qquad\n"
"a_c = \\frac{\\operatorname{cov}(H_c, H_g)}{\\operatorname{var}(H_g)},\n"
msgstr ""
"H_c \\;\\leftarrow\\; a_c\\, H_g + b_c, \\qquad\n"
"a_c = \\frac{\\operatorname{cov}(H_c, H_g)}{\\operatorname{var}(H_g)},\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:415
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"where the covariance and variance are local windowed statistics (a hard 3×3 box that does not\n"
"exclude clipped samples), and the division is simply skipped where the guide's variance falls\n"
"below $10^{-12}$ — there is no damping term. Because a detail band is\n"
"zero-mean, the intercept $b_c$ is essentially zero : the transfer moves *texture* from the guide to\n"
"the clipped channel, scaled by their measured local relationship.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:422
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**The chrominance diffusion.** The second stage operates on the RGB *ratios* (the chrominance,\n"
"$\\text{RGB}/n$ with $n = \\lVert \\text{RGB} \\rVert$, the euclidean norm — the symbol the\n"
"update rules below use), iterating the nine-point Oono & Puri Laplacian on each ratio plane ;\n"
"the norm plane $n$ rides the same pyramid but is explicitly protected from the step (backed up\n"
"and restored around it), so it is resynthesized as-is. That iteration is the gradient descent of an explicit variational problem : over the\n"
"clipped region $\\Omega$, with the valid rim as boundary data, it minimizes\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:423
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"E_{\\text{2021}}[u] \\;=\\; \\int_{\\Omega} \\lVert \\nabla u \\rVert^2 \\,\\mathrm{d}\\Omega\n"
"\\;+\\; \\lambda_{\\text{solid}} \\int_{\\Omega} \\lVert u - \\bar u \\rVert^2 \\,\\mathrm{d}\\Omega ,\n"
"\\qquad u\\big|_{\\partial\\Omega} = u_{\\text{valid}},\n"
msgstr ""
"E_{\\text{2021}}[u] \\;=\\; \\int_{\\Omega} \\lVert \\nabla u \\rVert^2 \\,\\mathrm{d}\\Omega\n"
"\\;+\\; \\lambda_{\\text{solid}} \\int_{\\Omega} \\lVert u - \\bar u \\rVert^2 \\,\\mathrm{d}\\Omega ,\n"
"\\qquad u\\big|_{\\partial\\Omega} = u_{\\text{valid}},\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:441
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"for each ratio plane and for the norm : a **Dirichlet (harmonic) energy** that carries the rim's\n"
"chrominance and level smoothly inward, plus an optional **screening term** pulling the core\n"
"toward the mean valid colour $\\bar u$ with the user's \"inpaint a flat color\" weight\n"
"$\\lambda_{\\text{solid}}$. Its Euler–Lagrange equation is the screened-Poisson equation of the\n"
"[theory section](#diffusion-as-color-inpainting) ; the 2021 code never solves it to steady\n"
"state — the \"iterations\" slider truncates the descent, so the practical result depends on the\n"
"iteration budget as much as on the energy. Two properties follow directly from this objective\n"
"and explain the method's signature look : a *harmonic* fill flattens (it penalizes gradients, so\n"
"the interior tends to a level plateau — the theory section shows why a *biharmonic* energy is\n"
"needed to continue slopes), and nothing in either stage constrains the reconstructed *level* of\n"
"a clipped channel, which stage 1 cannot transfer (zero-mean bands) and stage 2 only diffuses\n"
"from a rim that sits at the clip.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:442
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:772
#, no-wrap
msgid "The algorithm"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:445
#, no-wrap
msgid "The whole procedure, at a glance :\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (mermaid)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:446
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"flowchart TD\n"
"  A[\"raw mosaic (one colour per pixel)\"] --> B[\"bilinear interpolation to temporary RGB<br/>+ per-channel clip masks\"]\n"
"  B --> C[\"downsample 4× (for speed)\"]\n"
"  C --> D[\"à-trous B-spline pyramid:<br/>split into detail bands, one per frequency range\"]\n"
"  D --> E[\"per band, RGB, fine → coarse:<br/>guided-filter fit of the clipped channel<br/>against the most textured channel<br/>(validity not checked)<br/>→ transfer of TEXTURE (zero-mean details)\"]\n"
"  E --> F[\"per band, RGB ratios & norm, iterated 9-point Laplacian diffusion:<br/>spread structure from the valid rim<br/>into the blown core, isotropically\"]\n"
"  F --> G[\"optional: reaction toward a flat colour<br/>(user slider) + Poissonian re-graining\"]\n"
"  G --> H[\"upsample, remosaic,<br/>feathered composite over the raw\"]\n"
msgstr ""
"flowchart TD\n"
"  A[\"raw mosaic (one colour per pixel)\"] --> B[\"bilinear interpolation to temporary RGB<br/>+ per-channel clip masks\"]\n"
"  B --> C[\"downsample 4× (for speed)\"]\n"
"  C --> D[\"à-trous B-spline pyramid:<br/>split into detail bands, one per frequency range\"]\n"
"  D --> E[\"per band, RGB, fine → coarse:<br/>guided-filter fit of the clipped channel<br/>against the most textured channel<br/>(validity not checked)<br/>→ transfer of TEXTURE (zero-mean details)\"]\n"
"  E --> F[\"per band, RGB ratios & norm, iterated 9-point Laplacian diffusion:<br/>spread structure from the valid rim<br/>into the blown core, isotropically\"]\n"
"  F --> G[\"optional: reaction toward a flat colour<br/>(user slider) + Poissonian re-graining\"]\n"
"  G --> H[\"upsample, remosaic,<br/>feathered composite over the raw\"]\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:465
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The trade-offs are deliberate. Working on detail bands makes the transfer immune to white-balance\n"
"errors (only *shapes* move between channels). The nine-point Laplacian is the isotropic,\n"
"rotation-invariant discretization derived in [first principles](#gradients-and-laplacians), so\n"
"the diffusion fills the core from the outside in without following the pixel grid's axes.\n"
"Smoothness is always preferred over sharpness : an error in a blown highlight reads as a hard\n"
"artifact when sharp and as a plausible glow when soft. And the fine-to-coarse band order means\n"
"each band is fitted independently within one pass — there is no cross-scale consistency\n"
"constraint, which stays harmless precisely because the bands are zero-mean.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:467
#, no-wrap
msgid "Three preparatory stages deserve a note — they are shared by every reconstruction method in this article, the successor included.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:473
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**Bilinear demosaic.** The mosaic is bilinearly demosaiced to a temporary RGB image : a *throwaway*\n"
"demosaic whose only job is to give every channel a value everywhere for the per-channel guided fit;\n"
"the final output is remosaiced back to a single channel.\n"
"A per-channel **clip mask**, together with its logical OR (feathered into the compositing opacity\n"
"$\\alpha$), records which channels saturated.[^impl]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:478
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**Local channel normalization.** Each colour is divided by the *average value of that colour in the\n"
"current tile*, a crude local white balance computed on the spot. This equalizes channel magnitudes\n"
"so the guide-selection variance comparison is not biased toward whichever channel carries the\n"
"largest raw numbers; it deliberately does not reuse the white balance declared upstream.[^impl]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:486
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**Feathering the mask.** The binary mask is smoothed by a small $5\\times5$ box average into an\n"
"opacity $\\alpha \\in [0,1]$, used as the final compositing weight *and* as the per-channel soft\n"
"weights of the à-trous reconstruction below. Feathering softens the seam where the\n"
"reconstruction meets untouched pixels; in the [numerical tests](#results) it lowered this\n"
"method's boundary error rather than raising it — removing it was tested and measurably hurts\n"
"here (the soft weights are load-bearing), while the successor method drops feathering entirely\n"
"(its masks are binary end to end ; see [the graveyard](#annex--the-graveyard)).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:487
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1159
#, no-wrap
msgid "The update rules"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:497
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[The optimization problem](#the-optimization-problem) states what this method minimizes and\n"
"[the algorithm](#the-algorithm) narrates its stages ; here are the actual **signal updates** of\n"
"the shipped 2021 mode, in execution order, for an implementer starting from scratch. Planes :\n"
"the four-times-downsampled temporary RGB $u_c$ (bilinear demosaic, channel-normalized), the\n"
"feathered per-channel masks $\\alpha_c \\in [0,1]$ and their any-clip opacity $\\alpha$.\n"
"Decomposition : the [à-trous B-spline pyramid](#the-à-trous-b-spline-pyramid) with stride\n"
"$2^s$ per scale — cascaded blurs $\\mathrm{LF}_s$, detail bands\n"
"$D\\_s = \\mathrm{LF}\\_{s-1} - \\mathrm{LF}\\_s$, plus the coarsest residual.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:503
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**1. Texture transfer** (the RGB pass), per scale from fine to coarse, at every pixel where\n"
"$\\alpha > 0$. On the $3\\times3$ à-trous neighbourhood (stride $2^s$) of the detail band,\n"
"compute the per-channel patch mean and variance, pick the guide $g$ as the channel of\n"
"**largest patch variance** (validity is not checked — the root of failure 4), fit the\n"
"zero-intercept-biased colour-line on the details,\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:504
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"a_c = \\max\\!\\left( \\frac{\\operatorname{cov}(D_g, D_c)}{\\operatorname{var}(D_g)},\\, 0 \\right),\n"
"\\qquad\n"
"b_c = \\bar D_c - a_c\\, \\bar D_g,\n"
msgstr ""
"a_c = \\max\\!\\left( \\frac{\\operatorname{cov}(D_g, D_c)}{\\operatorname{var}(D_g)},\\, 0 \\right),\n"
"\\qquad\n"
"b_c = \\bar D_c - a_c\\, \\bar D_g,\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:515
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"and blend the prediction in, fading quadratically with the scale's equivalent radius — taken\n"
"at step $4s$, not $s$ : the code evaluates $\\sigma$ at `s * DS_FACTOR`, charging each scale for\n"
"the downscale factor as well, so the fade is far steeper than $\\sigma_s^2$ alone suggests\n"
"($\\beta$ is $\\alpha/380$ at $s{=}1$ and $\\alpha/97\\\\,000$ at $s{=}2$ — the guided transfer\n"
"effectively lives on the finest scales) :\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:516
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"D_c \\;\\leftarrow\\; \\beta_c \\,\\big(a_c\\, D_g + b_c\\big) + (1 - \\beta_c)\\, D_c,\n"
"\\qquad\n"
"\\beta_c = \\frac{\\alpha_c}{\\sigma_{G,\\,4s}^{2}}.\n"
msgstr ""
"D_c \\;\\leftarrow\\; \\beta_c \\,\\big(a_c\\, D_g + b_c\\big) + (1 - \\beta_c)\\, D_c,\n"
"\\qquad\n"
"\\beta_c = \\frac{\\alpha_c}{\\sigma_{G,\\,4s}^{2}}.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:526
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Resynthesis sums the processed bands plus the residual, clamped to $\\geq 0$ ; on the last\n"
"iteration, Poissonian grain of amplitude $\\sigma = u_c \\cdot \\texttt{noise\\_level}$ is folded in\n"
"(brightening only) under $\\alpha$. The result is split into direction and magnitude,\n"
"$r_c = u_c / \\lVert u \\rVert$ and $n = \\lVert u \\rVert$, for the next pass.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:532
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**2. Chrominance diffusion** (the chroma pass), same pyramid over the four planes\n"
"$(r_R, r_G, r_B, n)$ : each detail band of the three *ratio* planes takes one explicit Euler\n"
"step of the screened heat equation, per pixel where $\\alpha > 0$ and per channel — the norm\n"
"plane's band is backed up before the step and restored after it, so $n$ crosses the pyramid\n"
"undiffused,\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:533
#, no-wrap
msgid "D \\;\\leftarrow\\; D + \\alpha_c\\, \\kappa \\,\\big( \\mathbf{K}_{\\text{iso}} \\!*\\! D \\;-\\; \\lambda\\, D \\big),\n"
msgstr "D \\;\\leftarrow\\; D + \\alpha_c\\, \\kappa \\,\\big( \\mathbf{K}_{\\text{iso}} \\!*\\! D \\;-\\; \\lambda\\, D \\big),\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:542
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"with $\\mathbf{K}_{\\text{iso}}$ the nine-point isotropic Laplacian of\n"
"[first principles](#gradients-and-laplacians), $\\kappa = \\sigma_B^2 / (2\\sqrt{\\pi}) \\approx 0.31$\n"
"the band-to-Laplacian rescaling, and $\\lambda$ the flat-colour reaction (`solid_color`).\n"
"Resynthesis as above, then the ratios are renormalized to unit norm and recombined,\n"
"$u_c \\leftarrow r_c \\cdot n$.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:545
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**3. Iterate.** Passes 1–2 repeat `iterations` times (the user slider) ; nothing detects\n"
"convergence, the count is the budget.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:549
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**4. Composite.** The reconstruction is upsampled four times and blended over the raw mosaic\n"
"through the feathered opacity, per photosite of colour $c$ :\n"
"$\\text{out} = \\alpha\\\\, u_c + (1 - \\alpha)\\\\, \\text{raw}$.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:553
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Nothing else writes a pixel — and, as the ground-truth study found, nothing above transfers a\n"
"*level* : every update acts on zero-mean detail bands or on ratios, which is exactly the\n"
"structural gap [the successor closes](#the-new-method--harmonic-transposition).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:554
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1552
#, no-wrap
msgid "Implementation & optimizations"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:568
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The whole reconstruction runs on a **four-times-downsampled** buffer — one sixteenth of the\n"
"pixels — and the result is upsampled and composited back over the raw under a feathered mask.\n"
"That single decision buys most of the method's speed and costs measurable accuracy : re-running\n"
"the same mathematics at full resolution lowers boundary error by about 30 %, because the\n"
"upsampled reconstruction is blurry against the sharp original it must join (the successor method\n"
"runs at full resolution for exactly that reason). The à-trous detail bands over-evaluate the\n"
"Laplacian by a known constant (the B-spline's $\\sigma_B = 1.05537$ gives\n"
"$1/\\kappa = 3.1827$), which the diffusion step compensates ; the diffusion runs\n"
"`iterations` × (one RGB-ratio pass + one norm pass) per scale, on the whole frame — there is no\n"
"region segmentation, so cost scales with the image, not with the clipped area. Poissonian grain\n"
"($\\sigma = \\text{value} \\times \\text{noise level}$) is regenerated on the last iteration so\n"
"reconstructed areas do not look plastically smooth next to real texture.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:569
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1735
#, no-wrap
msgid "Problems discovered"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:573
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**What never happens in the flowchart above is a transfer of *level*** — an observation\n"
"invisible without ground truth, and where the whole 2026 study starts.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:587
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**The issues.** In practice, users kept reporting blown highlights that stayed magenta after\n"
"reconstruction — the very defect the method exists to fix. The study documented in the rest of\n"
"this article eventually located the root cause in the mathematics above : the guided fit was\n"
"applied to the **detail bands only**. A detail band has zero local mean, so the intercept $b_c$\n"
"carries no energy, and only texture ever transfers — never the *level*. The clipped channel's\n"
"low-frequency component, pinned at the clip value, was added back unchanged ; a blown channel was\n"
"left at the clip (or nudged below it by the chrominance handling) and stayed magenta. In the validation\n"
"bench built later, this original reconstruction is often *worse than doing nothing* on\n"
"single-channel clips : a root-mean-square error (RMSE) of 0.073 against 0.049 for leaving the pixels\n"
"clipped, on a natural-like scene where the eventual rebuild reaches 0.015 (these three numbers\n"
"come from the Python research prototype's bench — `fix_prototype.py` in the [research repository](https://github.com/aurelienpierre/guided-laplacian-highlights-research) —\n"
"whose NumPy port of the 2021 module stands in for the C ; the shipped implementations are\n"
"scored in [the results](#results)).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:593
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"{{% figure src=\"./synthetic-bug-fix.png\" %}}\n"
"A synthetic scene: three saturated single-channel highlights (red, green, blue disks) and a bright\n"
"near-neutral one. **Ground truth** is the unclipped scene, **clipped** what the sensor records,\n"
"**previous method** the Python port of the 2021 à-trous module, **corrected method** the same design with the\n"
"full-signal repair described just below.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:601
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In the single-channel disks the corrected result climbs back toward the true colour (e.g. the\n"
"red disk recovers $\\approx 1.7$ vs. true $\\approx 1.9$, with green and blue matched exactly) where the\n"
"previous method stays *below* the clip ($\\approx 0.9$). The all-clipped neutral disk, flat at\n"
"the clip in both the sensor and the previous method, is re-domed by the shared luminance fill\n"
"(centre $\\approx 1.5$ vs. true $\\approx 1.6$) and stays near-neutral, its chrominance carried by the\n"
"rim diffusion.\n"
"{{% /figure %}}\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:611
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The one-line repair — apply the same guided fit to the **full signal** (low frequency and detail\n"
"together) so the intercept carries the local mean and a blown channel can rise above the clip\n"
"(the math is in [the update rules](#the-update-rules-1)) —\n"
"fixes that class of failures, and it is the foundation everything later kept : all subsequent\n"
"methods in this article fit colour-lines on full values. It was\n"
"**necessary but not sufficient**. With ground truth to measure against — on the repaired\n"
"design, rebuilt at full resolution around a ladder of window sizes (the\n"
"[graveyard annex](#annex--the-graveyard) details it) — four\n"
"*structural* failures remained, and they shaped the successor method :\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:617
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"*First*, the window ladder degenerates wherever a window sees mostly clip-level data (fine\n"
"windows near the rim, coarse windows deep inside the hole), and a degenerate fit (covariance\n"
"near zero, slope near zero) fills flat, at roughly the clip level. Worse, the hand-off between\n"
"consecutive scales follows a contour of constant depth into the hole, and the two scales'\n"
"disagreement prints a visible **arc** along it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:622
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"*Second*, the $\\epsilon$ damping above competes with the guide's local variance, so it silently\n"
"crushes the slope wherever that variance is small — which protects noisy content by accident and\n"
"flattens clean smooth gradients (like sky) by the same mechanism. One constant, two opposite\n"
"consequences, no value that serves both.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:628
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"*Third*, the sensor does not clip abruptly : it compresses the last few percent below\n"
"saturation, so the band of pixels the reconstruction treats as trusted anchors is recorded\n"
"systematically **too low**.[^knee-sensor] Even an oracle that rebuilt the clipped interior *exactly* would\n"
"then sit visibly brighter than the biased ring it must attach to : the seam is in the data, not\n"
"in the estimate, and only correcting the data (the knee inversion) can remove it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:635
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"*Fourth*, the whole method rests on one hypothesis : neighbouring channels rise and fall\n"
"together, so a clipped channel is a measurable affine function of a surviving one. And some\n"
"content (a sky whose hue itself drifts, iridescence, colour texture finer than the window)\n"
"simply does not satisfy it. There, the guide contains no information about the missing channel\n"
"*for any estimator*, so the design must measure that ($R^2$) and change the information source\n"
"altogether : spatial smoothness instead of inter-channel transfer.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:637
#, no-wrap
msgid "Fixing those took more than a fix — it took a change of paradigm.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:638
#, no-wrap
msgid "The new method : harmonic transposition"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:651
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This section documents the method that ships today — its premises, its optimization problem,\n"
"its algorithm, and how the production implementation drifts from the research prototype.\n"
"Measured results, performance, and the general findings each have their own section below.\n"
"Harmonic transposition ships as its **own reconstruction mode** next to the original\n"
"`guided laplacians` : the 2021 à-trous method keeps its historical name and design —\n"
"unchanged except for the shared border-gather fix, which improves its own scores — and the new\n"
"method is an explicit opt-in.\n"
"The reconstruction core is agnostic to the sensor mosaic and runs on Bayer and X-Trans alike, on\n"
"the processor and inside an OpenCL pipe, where each clipped region is\n"
"solved on whichever side of the bus measured faster\n"
"(see [the performance section](#performance)).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:668
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The repair above changes what the guided filter *transfers* ; harmonic transposition changes how\n"
"the model **travels**. Wherever at least one channel survived, reconstruction is a regression\n"
"problem, not an inpainting problem : the valid channels are measured data, present at every\n"
"pixel of the blown zone, and the only unknown is the local *relationship* (the colour-line)\n"
"between them and the clipped channel. The 2021 method — and its corrected, full-signal rebuild —\n"
"evaluated that relationship wherever a statistics window could reach, and stitched the\n"
"evaluations together ; every stitch was a seam, and windows deep inside a large hole reached\n"
"nothing at all. Harmonic transposition inverts the transport : fit the colour-line **once**,\n"
"where the data supports it, then diffuse the *coefficients* of the model — not the pixel\n"
"values — across the blown zone as smooth fields, and only then evaluate them against the\n"
"measured surviving channels at every pixel. Coefficients are smooth by nature where values are\n"
"not ; the guides re-inject the full-resolution structure at evaluation time. Why this is a\n"
"difference in kind rather than degree — and what it generalizes to — is spelled out in the\n"
"[theoretical findings](#theoretical-findings).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:678
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Everything else the 2021 method got right is kept, on a sounder footing : the colour-line model\n"
"and its windowed weighted least squares (the guided filter's regression), the biharmonic dome for guide-less magnitude, chrominance carried as bounded ratios,\n"
"the preference for smooth continuations, and the grain regeneration. What is new besides the\n"
"transport : per-region segmentation at **full resolution** (cost scales with the clipped area,\n"
"not the image), a measured **sensor-rolloff inversion** that debiases the near-clip band before\n"
"anything is fitted (failure 3 above), fits gated and trusted by their own measured quality\n"
"$R^2$ (failure 4), and one design rule applied everywhere, derived from the seam-energy law of\n"
"the [theoretical findings](#theoretical-findings) : **no step may hand off\n"
"between estimators that disagree** (failure 1).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:685
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Neither step assembles a global energy and calls a named solver, but each *is* the local update rule\n"
"of a variational problem, and together they make the objective explicit. On the clipped region\n"
"$\\Omega$ the reconstruction minimizes four coupled energies on the model.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:688
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**1. Cross-channel affine consistency.** Where a valid guide $g$ exists, each clipped channel should\n"
"be an affine function of the guide : the guided filter is the exact minimizer of\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:689
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"E_{\\text{affine}} = \\sum_{\\omega}\\sum_{c}\\sum_{i \\in \\omega}\n"
"w_i \\Big[ \\big( a_{c} \\, u_g(i) + b_{c} - u_c(i) \\big)^2 + \\varepsilon\\, a_{c}^2 \\Big],\n"
"\\qquad w_i = [\\,i \\text{ valid}\\,].\n"
msgstr ""
"E_{\\text{affine}} = \\sum_{\\omega}\\sum_{c}\\sum_{i \\in \\omega}\n"
"w_i \\Big[ \\big( a_{c} \\, u_g(i) + b_{c} - u_c(i) \\big)^2 + \\varepsilon\\, a_{c}^2 \\Big],\n"
"\\qquad w_i = [\\,i \\text{ valid}\\,].\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:702
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Fitting on the full values $u$ (not the detail) is what makes the minimizer carry the local average, so\n"
"$E_{\\text{affine}}$ recovers **magnitude and texture together**.[^he][^colorline] This term is\n"
"trusted in proportion to the fit's **squared** correlation $(R^2)^2$; where $R^2 \\to 0$ the channel is\n"
"instead held to its own second-order smoothness (a per-channel biharmonic term $\\int_\\Omega\n"
"(\\Delta u_c)^2\\, \\mathrm{d}\\Omega$), so the objective never rewards a colour-line the data do not support. The\n"
"squaring sharpens that trade so a middling correlation leans on the smooth fallback rather than a\n"
"discontinuous cross-channel guess.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:707
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**1b. Anisotropic coefficient transport (the shipped form of term 1).** The affine fit of\n"
"term 1 defines its coefficients only where a window holds enough trusted data ; across the rest\n"
"of the blown zone the *model itself* is the unknown. The shipped method extends it by minimizing\n"
"an anisotropic Dirichlet energy on the coefficient planes,\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:708
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"E_{\\text{transport}} \\;=\\; \\sum_{p \\,\\in\\, \\{a,\\, b,\\, d,\\, R^2\\}}\n"
"\\int_{\\Omega} \\nabla p^{\\top} D \\,\\nabla p \\;\\mathrm{d}\\Omega,\n"
"\\qquad p\\big|_{\\text{anchors}} = p_{\\text{fit}},\n"
msgstr ""
"E_{\\text{transport}} \\;=\\; \\sum_{p \\,\\in\\, \\{a,\\, b,\\, d,\\, R^2\\}}\n"
"\\int_{\\Omega} \\nabla p^{\\top} D \\,\\nabla p \\;\\mathrm{d}\\Omega,\n"
"\\qquad p\\big|_{\\text{anchors}} = p_{\\text{fit}},\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:723
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"where the anchors are the gated fits of term 1 (enough trusted mass, $R^2 > 0.25$, bounded\n"
"slopes) and $D$ is the variance-adaptive steering tensor of\n"
"[step 3](#the-algorithm-1), built from the measured guide\n"
"structure : gradient-dominant on a clean halo ramp (the model travels radially inward from the\n"
"rim), isophote-dominant where a hard edge crosses the zone (colour-lines must not mix across an\n"
"object boundary). Its Euler–Lagrange equation $\\operatorname{div}(D \\\\, \\nabla p) = 0$ is the\n"
"steered fill ; with $D = I$ it reduces to the plain harmonic fill. The evaluation\n"
"$\\hat u_c = a\\\\,u_{g_1} + b\\\\,u_{g_2} + d$ against the *measured* guides closes the term : the\n"
"energy transports the model, and the data restores the detail.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:729
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**2. Magnitude curvature (fallback).** Where no guide survives, fine detail is lost but the\n"
"low-frequency shape is not: it should *continue* the surrounding curvature rather than flatten. For a\n"
"partially-clipped channel this is the per-channel biharmonic term $\\int_\\Omega (\\Delta u_c)^2\\,\n"
"\\mathrm{d}\\Omega$ already invoked above. For the all-clipped core it is applied\n"
"**once** to the summed luminance $L_\\text{sum} = R+G+B$, one shared dome instead of three divergent ones:\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:730
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"E_{\\text{bihar}} = \\int_\\Omega (\\Delta L_\\text{sum})^2\\,\\mathrm{d}\\Omega,\n"
"\\qquad \\Delta^2 L_\\text{sum} = 0,\n"
"\\qquad L_\\text{sum}\\big|_{\\partial \\Omega} = L_{\\text{sum}}^{\\text{valid}} ,\n"
msgstr ""
"E_{\\text{bihar}} = \\int_\\Omega (\\Delta L_\\text{sum})^2\\,\\mathrm{d}\\Omega,\n"
"\\qquad \\Delta^2 L_\\text{sum} = 0,\n"
"\\qquad L_\\text{sum}\\big|_{\\partial \\Omega} = L_{\\text{sum}}^{\\text{valid}} ,\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:738
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"anchored to the core's true valid rim; its Euler–Lagrange equation $\\Delta^2 L = 0$ is the domed fill\n"
"above.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:741
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**3. Chrominance smoothness (fallback).** Where no guide survives, the reconstructed ratios\n"
"$r = \\text{RGB}/L_\\text{sum}$ should be smooth and match the rim, optionally biased toward flatness:\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:742
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"E_{\\text{chrominance}} = \\int_\\Omega \\Big( \\lVert \\nabla r \\rVert^2 + \\lambda \\, \\lVert r \\rVert^2 \\Big)\\, \\mathrm{d} \\Omega,\n"
"\\qquad\n"
"r\\big|_{\\partial \\Omega} = r_{\\text{valid}} .\n"
msgstr ""
"E_{\\text{chrominance}} = \\int_\\Omega \\Big( \\lVert \\nabla r \\rVert^2 + \\lambda \\, \\lVert r \\rVert^2 \\Big)\\, \\mathrm{d} \\Omega,\n"
"\\qquad\n"
"r\\big|_{\\partial \\Omega} = r_{\\text{valid}} .\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:750
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Its Euler–Lagrange equation is the screened-Poisson equation the diffusion integrates,[^qin] and the\n"
"recombination $\\text{RGB} = L\\cdot r$ closes the joint fill.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:771
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The energies act on **complementary pixels** : the affine term where a channel survives (weighted\n"
"by its correlation $R^2$), the per-channel biharmonic term where it does not, and the shared\n"
"luminance dome plus chrominance diffusion only in the all-clipped cores — the latter minimized\n"
"**subject to an inequality** : the diffused ratio of a clipped channel can never drop below its\n"
"saturation floor in ratio space, $r_c \\geq c_{0,c}/L_\\text{sum}$, which turns the chrominance term into an\n"
"obstacle problem (the math is in\n"
"[the chrominance subsection](#chrominance-by-diffusion)). The reconstructable set itself is\n"
"per channel : $\\Omega_c$ holds the pixels above the clip threshold — extended down to $0.9$ of\n"
"it for channels whose sensor rolloff engaged (the band override of\n"
"[step 2](#the-algorithm-1)), where the floor $c_{0,c}$ is the knee-corrected measurement rather\n"
"than the saturated reading. Each energy is minimized\n"
"by its own stage : the affine term by the guided fits (one window sized to the region's\n"
"reconstruction radius) ; the transport term by the anchored, steered relaxation of step 3 ; the\n"
"smoothness terms by their direct linear solves. There is deliberately no posterior smoothing\n"
"energy acting on the output : an earlier design ironed seams after the fact with an\n"
"uncertainty-weighted regularizer, and retiring it is the point — the seams are never created\n"
"(see [the graveyard](#annex--the-graveyard)).\n"
"This is the same\n"
"engineering philosophy as *diffuse or sharpen*: a stack of local, physically-motivated update rules\n"
"whose combined fixed point is the reconstruction, rather than one monolithic inverse problem.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:778
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Everything happens on the raw mosaic, in linear scene-referred RGB, before demosaicing, and at full\n"
"resolution. The method rebuilds each clipped channel from the channels that *survived* (along the\n"
"local colour-line, trusting it in proportion to how well it actually holds), and where **no** channel\n"
"survived it rebuilds one joint luminance dome and carries the surrounding chrominance inward.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:787
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The mosaic preparation — bilinear demosaic to a throwaway RGB, local channel\n"
"normalization, and the per-channel clip mask — is shared with the 2021 method and described\n"
"[in its algorithm section](#the-algorithm), with one addition and three refinements. The\n"
"addition : for the all-clipped cores a scalar **magnitude** $L_\\text{sum}$ (the summed luminance $R+G+B$)\n"
"is split from the **chrominance** $\\text{RGB}/L_\\text{sum}$ — each channel divided by the summed luminance, a\n"
"bounded, brightness-free description of the colour that this article uses consistently under\n"
"that name — so the two can be reconstructed by different means : a dome for the magnitude,\n"
"diffusion for the chrominance. The refinements, each traced from a measured rim artifact :\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:809
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"* **masks are binary, end to end.** The 2021 mode feathers its mask ; the successor keeps\n"
"  every validity and compositing mask hard (its one smooth weight is the joint core's\n"
"  blurred hand-over, step 7 of the algorithm, which blends two *reconstructions* — it never\n"
"  reclassifies measurements). The per-channel validity masks gate every fit and evaluation, and feathering them\n"
"  reclassified rim-clipped photosites — whose raw values sit at the detection threshold, biased\n"
"  low under sensor rolloff — as valid anchors on oblique contours, dragging the rim\n"
"  reconstruction toward the clip level (a $\\sim 10$ px sagging ramp against ground truth). The\n"
"  compositing weight is a hard switch : valid photosites keep their measurement exactly,\n"
"  clipped photosites take the pure reconstruction (a feathered alpha was measured to change\n"
"  nothing once the two fixes on this list are in — the retirement is documented in\n"
"  [the graveyard](#annex--the-graveyard)).\n"
"* **clipped raw values are floors, never blend targets.** On clipped photosites the raw\n"
"  reading is a lower bound, not a measurement : the composite writes\n"
"  $\\max(\\text{raw}, \\text{reconstruction})$, never a blend toward the biased reading (the old\n"
"  feathered blend printed a V-shaped dip through the raw value at every contour).\n"
"* **borders mirror.** The bilinear gather's border ring used to copy the centre photosite into\n"
"  all three channels and key all three clip flags on the centre's own channel — corrupted\n"
"  guides and dashed masks along the first and last rows and columns, which anchored the\n"
"  border-row fits at the clip level. Reflected neighbour indexing (the Bayer pattern is\n"
"  2-periodic, so mirroring preserves each neighbour's colour) restores the interior logic on\n"
"  the borders ; this fix is shared with the 2021 mode.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:813
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Every ground-truth scene improved on both metrics from these three refinements alone — the\n"
"rolloff sky's error dropped by a third — because the bench's rim rings are exactly where\n"
"biased anchors used to leak in.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:821
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The reconstruction's conceptual goal can be stated in one sentence : **wherever at least one channel survived, reconstruction is a regression\n"
"problem, not an inpainting problem** : the valid channels are measured data, present at every\n"
"pixel of the clipped zone, carrying the true structure of the scene. The algorithm's one design\n"
"rule, learned the hard way, is that **no step may hand off between estimators that disagree**\n"
"(the [seam-energy law](#theoretical-findings) of the theoretical findings).\n"
"Every stage below is therefore either seam-free by construction, or debiases the data\n"
"so that the estimators agree.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:823
#, no-wrap
msgid "The step-by-step procedure, as implemented in `process_harmonic_bayer` (and its X-Trans twin) :\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:825
#, no-wrap
msgid "The numbers in the graph refer to the steps detailed below it.\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (mermaid)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:826
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"flowchart TD\n"
"  subgraph P [\"once per image\"]\n"
"    direction TB\n"
"    A[\"raw mosaic\"] --> B[\"1 · interpolate<br/>+ clip masks\"]\n"
"    B --> K[\"2 · knee inversion\"]\n"
"    K --> S[\"1 · depth map<br/>+ segmentation\"]\n"
"  end\n"
"  subgraph R [\"for each clipped region\"]\n"
"    direction TB\n"
"    CF[\"3 · colour-line fits<br/>(magnitude + texture)\"] --> HF[\"4 · fine-detail refit\"]\n"
"    HF --> SD[\"5–6 · floors<br/>+ self-dome\"]\n"
"    SD --> JC[\"7 · all-clipped core\"]\n"
"    JC --> AN[\"8 · chrominance coherence\"]\n"
"  end\n"
"  S --> CF\n"
"  AN --> O[\"remosaic + composite\"]\n"
msgstr ""
"flowchart TD\n"
"  subgraph P [\"once per image\"]\n"
"    direction TB\n"
"    A[\"raw mosaic\"] --> B[\"1 · interpolate<br/>+ clip masks\"]\n"
"    B --> K[\"2 · knee inversion\"]\n"
"    K --> S[\"1 · depth map<br/>+ segmentation\"]\n"
"  end\n"
"  subgraph R [\"for each clipped region\"]\n"
"    direction TB\n"
"    CF[\"3 · colour-line fits<br/>(magnitude + texture)\"] --> HF[\"4 · fine-detail refit\"]\n"
"    HF --> SD[\"5–6 · floors<br/>+ self-dome\"]\n"
"    SD --> JC[\"7 · all-clipped core\"]\n"
"    JC --> AN[\"8 · chrominance coherence\"]\n"
"  end\n"
"  S --> CF\n"
"  AN --> O[\"remosaic + composite\"]\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:852
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**1. Detection, interpolation, segmentation.** The raw\n"
"colour-filter-array mosaic is bilinearly interpolated, with per-channel clip flags raised at\n"
"$0.995\\\\,c$ for clip level $c$ and a binary per-channel validity mask ; the Euclidean distance transform\n"
"then gives each pixel its depth $\\delta$ inside the clipped zone, and connected-component\n"
"segmentation groups the clipped pixels into regions, each carrying its distance-transform\n"
"reconstruction radius.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:864
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**2. Sensor rolloff (knee) inversion.** Real sensors compress the last few percent below\n"
"saturation, so the near-clip band $[0.8\\\\,c, 0.995\\\\,c)$ holds values **biased low**. (The band is cut\n"
"generously : on sensors that clip hard rather than roll off, the no-op guarantee below makes the\n"
"extra width free.) The\n"
"reconstruction extrapolates *unbiased* estimates over this band, so the two disagree at the\n"
"detection contour : a seam no weighting can remove. The fix debiases the data itself : a windowed\n"
"joint regression predicts each band value from the fully-trusted channels, the (measured,\n"
"predicted) pairs are pooled into 24 bins over the band, and the per-bin median lift is accepted\n"
"only when statistically significant — median above twice its standard error, a $\\approx 95\\\\,\\\\%$\n"
"confidence gate, with at least 100 votes so the error estimate itself is stable ; 24 bins is as\n"
"fine as the band can be cut while keeping every bin that populated :\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:865
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\hat{k}^{-1}(v) = v + \\operatorname{median}\\big\\{\\, \\hat v_i - v_i \\;\\big|\\; v_i \\in \\text{bin}(v) \\,\\big\\}\n"
msgstr "\\hat{k}^{-1}(v) = v + \\operatorname{median}\\big\\{\\, \\hat v_i - v_i \\;\\big|\\; v_i \\in \\text{bin}(v) \\,\\big\\}\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:883
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"where $k$ is the sensor's unknown compression, so $\\hat{k}^{-1}$ is the\n"
"estimated *correction* — the function that takes a measured value $v$ from the band and returns\n"
"what the sensor should have recorded. The $v_i$ are all the measured band pixels whose value\n"
"falls in the same bin as $v$ ; each $\\hat v_i$ is what the\n"
"colour-line regression predicts that pixel *should* be, judging from its fully-trusted\n"
"neighbouring channels. Their difference $\\hat v_i - v_i$ is one pixel's vote on how much the\n"
"sensor under-recorded at that level, and the bin's correction is the **median** of its votes —\n"
"robust to the outliers a mean would follow. The resulting curve is then made monotone and\n"
"raise-only. On hard-clipped (unbiased) data every bin median is zero within\n"
"noise, so the correction has a **no-op guarantee**, verified bit-exact on the four hard-clip\n"
"synthetic cases, while on `pk1synth` (the one synthetic scene generated *with* an analytic\n"
"sensor rolloff, so its ground truth traces the real knee) the blind estimate matches the true\n"
"curve to a root-mean-square error of $7\\cdot10^{-4}$ on the green channel and $1.8\\cdot10^{-3}$\n"
"on the sparser red one :\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:891
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"{{< plotly title=\"The blind knee estimate against the ground truth, on the one synthetic scene with an analytic sensor rolloff (pk1synth). Circles : the true corrected value, read from the (ground truth, clipped) pixel pairs, per measured-value bin. Lines : what the estimator infers from the clipped mosaic alone, never having seen the truth. The dotted diagonal is the identity — a sensor with no rolloff. Reproduce with make_knee_figure.py.\" src=\"knee-estimate.json\" caption=\"true\" >}}\n"
" Two implementation details matter : estimation runs on a $2\\times 2$\n"
"**quad-binned copy of the raw mosaic** (each 2×2 Bayer cell yields one co-located red, green\n"
"(averaged) and blue sample), never on the bilinear interpolation : the interpolation samples each\n"
"channel through a different spatial filter depending on its position in the mosaic pattern, and\n"
"that alternating error is the same size as the knee signal it would drown ; and the correction is applied both to the reconstruction anchors and\n"
"to the composited output, while clip *detection* stays keyed on the measured values.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:908
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**The band override.** The lift restores the band's *level*, but a value-map cannot restore a\n"
"*slope* the sensor never recorded : where the compression flattened the band to a near-constant,\n"
"the lifted band is a near-constant too, and its junction with the rising reconstruction prints a\n"
"fine double contour under edge magnification (the band is measurably $7$–$14\\times$ flatter than\n"
"ground truth, bracketed by two gradient spikes). The information is not lost, though — the\n"
"*guides* are unclipped through the band and carry the true slope. So for every channel whose\n"
"rolloff **engaged**, the detection extends below the threshold into the deep band : those pixels\n"
"are reconstructed by the colour-line model like any clipped pixel, with their knee-lifted\n"
"measurement as their per-pixel saturation floor, and the fits anchor on knee-corrected data\n"
"below the band. The floor makes the override conservative by construction — on noisy real\n"
"images the model rarely exceeds the lifted measurement, and the output stays pixel-identical ;\n"
"on the rolloff bench scene, where the model genuinely knows the slope, the zone error drops\n"
"another factor of five when the override lands (RMSE $0.012 \\to 0.0025$ measured then ;\n"
"$0.0053$ in the shipped build, after the later compositing rounds took their own bites) and\n"
"the contour gradient profile becomes indistinguishable from ground truth. Channels without a measured rolloff keep the plain\n"
"detection : on hard-clipping sensors the band is trustworthy data and stays anchored.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:916
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**3. The coefficient field.** For each clipped channel $v$ with guides $u_1, u_2$, a windowed\n"
"weighted least-squares fit is computed at a single scale $\\sigma = \\operatorname{clip}(r/6, 8, 64)$\n"
"(with $r$ the region's reconstruction radius — the window's $\\pm 3\\sigma$ support then spans the\n"
"radius, so even the deepest pixel's fit reaches valid data ; the floor keeps enough samples for\n"
"a stable fit on tiny regions, and the cap bounds the cost of huge ones), over the pixels where\n"
"all three channels are valid :\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:917
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\\begin{aligned}\n"
"(a, b, d)(x) &= \\arg\\min_{a,b,d} \\sum_y w(y)\\, G_\\sigma(x - y)\\,\n"
"                 \\big( v(y) - a\\, u_1(y) - b\\, u_2(y) - d \\big)^2 \\\\\n"
"\\hat v(x) &= a(x)\\, u_1(x) + b(x)\\, u_2(x) + d(x)\n"
"\\end{aligned}\n"
msgstr ""
"\\begin{aligned}\n"
"(a, b, d)(x) &= \\arg\\min_{a,b,d} \\sum_y w(y)\\, G_\\sigma(x - y)\\,\n"
"                 \\big( v(y) - a\\, u_1(y) - b\\, u_2(y) - d \\big)^2 \\\\\n"
"\\hat v(x) &= a(x)\\, u_1(x) + b(x)\\, u_2(x) + d(x)\n"
"\\end{aligned}\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:944
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"where $x$ is the pixel whose local model is being built and $y$ runs over its\n"
"neighbours. The window $G_\\sigma(x-y)$ is a Gaussian that weighs neighbours by distance\n"
"(full weight nearby, fading over roughly $\\sigma$ pixels), and $w(y)$ is the trust mask — one on\n"
"pixels where all three channels hold real measurements, zero elsewhere, so clipped pixels never\n"
"vote. The first line asks, at every $x$ : which slopes $a, b$ on the two guides and which offset\n"
"$d$ best explain the clipped channel on the trusted neighbourhood ? The second line then *uses*\n"
"that local model : the estimate $\\hat v(x)$ reads the two guides at $x$ itself and maps them\n"
"through the fitted relation. In practice the minimization is never run per pixel — it is\n"
"solved from ten blurred moment planes (a trusted-mass count, three means, six second\n"
"moments, gathered in three four-channel blurs) through the $2\\times2$ normal equations. The\n"
"moments are accumulated **about each channel's per-region mean** : in float arithmetic the raw\n"
"$E[u^2] - E[u]^2$ form cancels catastrophically on smooth content (the squared mean dwarfs the\n"
"variance) and the fit's division amplifies the surviving digits into device-dependent slope\n"
"noise — centering removes the cancellation, and the slopes and $R^2$ are invariant under the\n"
"shift while the intercept is unshifted right after the fit. The system is solved with a **relative**\n"
"Tikhonov (ridge) damping $\\lambda = 10^{-3}\\\\,(\\operatorname{var} u_1 + \\operatorname{var} u_2)/2$ that\n"
"scales with the signal instead of eating weak-but-real slopes. The $10^{-3}$ is the\n"
"smallest factor that stabilized degenerate windows on the bench — anything larger starts\n"
"flattening real slopes. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:970
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The novelty is what happens next :\n"
"instead of evaluating each pixel with whatever fit its own window could reach (the ladder's way),\n"
"the **coefficient planes themselves are diffused across the clipped zone, steered by the\n"
"measured guide structure**, and only\n"
"then evaluated against the measured guides. Coefficients are smooth by nature where values are\n"
"not : diffusing them transports the *model* into the zone, and the evaluation restores the full\n"
"local structure carried by the valid channels. No scales, no depth gates, no level-set writes\n"
"(no rings of equal depth stamped separately) —\n"
"no seams, by construction. This transport of the *model* rather than the content is the\n"
"article's most transportable idea, and how it differs in kind from the guided filter's own\n"
"coefficient blur is stated in\n"
"[Three results we believe are general](#theoretical-findings). A pixel\n"
"qualifies as a diffusion **anchor** only if its window held\n"
"enough trusted mass *and* its fit is sane : the fit's $R^2$, the *coefficient of determination*,\n"
"is the share of the channel's local variance that the colour-line explains (1 means the guides\n"
"predict the channel perfectly, 0 means not at all), and anchors require $R^2 > 0.25$ with bounded\n"
"slopes. Both gates are calibrated from measurements, not taste : content with **no colour-line\n"
"at all** still scores $R^2 \\approx 0.25$–$0.6$ (against $\\approx 0.9$ where the colour-line is\n"
"real), so the gate only rejects fits worse than pure decorrelation — numerical accidents, not\n"
"weak models ; and physical colour-line slopes are bounded by the channels' saturation ratios\n"
"(under $4$ on every camera measured), so the $|a| < 64$ bound sits an order of magnitude above\n"
"anything physical, and only degenerate near-zero-variance windows — whose exploding slopes\n"
"would poison the diffusion boundary — ever trip it.\n"
"The diffusion is a coarse-to-fine **Jacobi fill** : each unknown is repeatedly replaced by the\n"
"average its neighbours imply. Three terms carry the whole scheme :\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:980
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"* **Cell.** The fill does not run per pixel. The coefficient planes live on a coarse grid of\n"
"  pitch $\\sigma/4$ (clamped to at most $8$ px), and a cell is one node of that grid — one\n"
"  $\\sigma/4$-sized block of pixels. The coefficients come out of $\\sigma$-wide fit windows,\n"
"  so four cells per $\\sigma$ oversample them, and the pitch clamp bounds the final bilinear\n"
"  upsampling error.\n"
"* **Anchor.** A cell whose fit window passed the trust gates above — it holds a coefficient\n"
"  actually measured on valid data.\n"
"* **Pinned.** The sweeps treat anchors as fixed boundary data and only ever rewrite the\n"
"  *unknown* cells between them.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:985
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This shape is chosen for robustness. A float conjugate-gradient on the near-singular\n"
"pure-harmonic system diverges stochastically when the zone reaches the region border. Jacobi\n"
"with pinned anchors cannot : each update is an average of neighbours, so the relaxation obeys\n"
"the maximum principle — no unknown can ever leave the range of the anchor values.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:994
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Convergence comes from the pyramid's depth, not from the sweep count. The coarsest level starts\n"
"from a flat anchor mean — the farthest possible state from the solution — and Jacobi's slowest\n"
"error mode on a hole $N$ cells wide decays in $\\mathcal{O}(N^2)$ sweeps. So the pyramid keeps\n"
"halving until the coarsest grid's long side is at most $8$ cells ($8^2 = 64$ sweeps to relax,\n"
"comfortably inside the budget), and every level then runs the same flat $100$ sweeps — the\n"
"finer levels only correct local interpolation error. A shallower pyramid with a fixed count\n"
"measurably truncated the fill on deep holes — the numbers are in\n"
"[the general results below](#theoretical-findings).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1003
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"{{< note >}}\n"
"This is the method's **one remaining pyramid**, and it belongs to the *fill* — the transport of\n"
"already-fitted coefficients. It is unrelated to the fitting windows, which use a single\n"
"radius-derived $\\sigma$ per region (multi-scale windows exist only inside the knee estimator),\n"
"and it is not the retired trace-form chroma pyramid of the all-clip core, which the\n"
"divergence-form direct solve replaced and which survives only as the fallback for cores above\n"
"$2^{14}$ unknowns.\n"
"{{< /note >}}\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1011
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The transport itself is **not uniform either : it is steered by the measured guide structure**.\n"
"A steering plane $L_\\text{mean}$ — the mean of the *valid* channels wherever at least one survives, the\n"
"flat plateau mean in the all-clip core (where the tensor then degenerates to the identity) ;\n"
"this is a **different luminance** from the summed magnitude $L_\\text{sum}$ that the dome and the\n"
"ratios use — is\n"
"downsampled to each pyramid level, and the neighbour averages are weighted by the anisotropic\n"
"tensor\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1012
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"D \\;=\\; \\big[\\, m + (1-m)\\,c_2 \\,\\big]\\; t\\,t^{\\top}\n"
"\\;+\\; \\big[\\, m\\,c_2 + (1-m) \\,\\big]\\; g\\,g^{\\top},\n"
"\\qquad c_2 = e^{-\\lVert\\nabla L_\\text{mean}\\rVert / (4\\,\\langle\\lVert\\nabla L_\\text{mean}\\rVert\\rangle)},\n"
msgstr ""
"D \\;=\\; \\big[\\, m + (1-m)\\,c_2 \\,\\big]\\; t\\,t^{\\top}\n"
"\\;+\\; \\big[\\, m\\,c_2 + (1-m) \\,\\big]\\; g\\,g^{\\top},\n"
"\\qquad c_2 = e^{-\\lVert\\nabla L_\\text{mean}\\rVert / (4\\,\\langle\\lVert\\nabla L_\\text{mean}\\rVert\\rangle)},\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1026
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"where $g$ is the unit gradient direction of $L_\\text{mean}$ (uphill), $t$ the unit isophote\n"
"direction, and $\\langle\\lVert\\nabla L_\\text{mean}\\rVert\\rangle$ the gradient magnitude averaged\n"
"over the region — the normalization that makes the damping exposure-independent —\n"
"(along the level lines), and $c_2$ the same edge-crossing damping as the\n"
"[step-8 chrominance pass](#diffusion-as-color-inpainting). Normalizing the gradient by its own\n"
"regional mean makes that damping scale-free — only gradients well above the halo's average read\n"
"as boundaries, the $4$ setting how soft the reading is. The blend weight $m \\in [0, 1]$ is\n"
"the **edge probability**, measured from the trend-corrected windowed variance of $L_\\text{mean}$ :\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1027
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"m = \\frac{v}{v + (k\\,\\bar L_\\text{mean})^2}, \\qquad\n"
"v = \\max\\!\\big(\\operatorname{var}_w(L_\\text{mean}) - \\tfrac{4}{3}\\lVert\\nabla L_\\text{mean}\\rVert^2,\\; 0\\big),\n"
"\\qquad k = 0.15,\n"
msgstr ""
"m = \\frac{v}{v + (k\\,\\bar L_\\text{mean})^2}, \\qquad\n"
"v = \\max\\!\\big(\\operatorname{var}_w(L_\\text{mean}) - \\tfrac{4}{3}\\lVert\\nabla L_\\text{mean}\\rVert^2,\\; 0\\big),\n"
"\\qquad k = 0.15,\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1058
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"where $\\operatorname{var}\\_w$ and $\\bar L\\_\\text{mean}$ are the windowed variance and mean of the steering\n"
"plane, and the $\\tfrac{4}{3}\\lVert\\nabla L\\_\\text{mean}\\rVert^2$ term subtracts the variance the local\n"
"*ramp* explains : a pure ramp of slope $\\nabla L\\_\\text{mean}$ seen through a window of spatial variance\n"
"$\\sigma_w^2$ has intensity variance $\\sigma_w^2 \\lVert\\nabla L\\_\\text{mean}\\rVert^2$, and the window\n"
"here (two $3\\times3$ box passes) has $\\sigma_w^2 = 2 \\cdot \\tfrac{2}{3} = \\tfrac{4}{3}$\n"
"per axis. A smooth halo gradient, however steep, therefore leaves no residual, while a hard\n"
"edge leaves variance no ramp can account for. The threshold $k$ — the relative contrast above\n"
"which residual texture is read as a boundary — is the one constant of the transport that could\n"
"not be derived, so it was calibrated by an **empirical fine sweep** on the six ground-truth\n"
"scenes : every scene stays at or below the isotropic error over the whole range\n"
"$k \\in [0.14, 0.25]$ (the design is not fragile to it), and $k = 0.15$ is the value that\n"
"improves every scene simultaneously and takes the occlusion win with margin. The two limits of\n"
"$m$ read naturally. On a clean halo ramp ($m \\to 0$),\n"
"$D \\to g\\\\,g^{\\top} + c_2\\\\,t\\\\,t^{\\top}$ : the model travels **radially**, along the\n"
"brightness ramp from the rim inward, where its information actually lives. Where a hard edge\n"
"crosses the blown zone ($m \\to 1$), $D \\to t\\\\,t^{\\top} + c_2\\\\,g\\\\,g^{\\top}$ with $c_2$\n"
"small : the transport runs **along the boundary and refuses to cross it** — an edge inside the\n"
"zone means the content beyond follows another colour-line, and mixing the two models across it\n"
"is exactly the occlusion failure the graveyard documents. The discretization uses the\n"
"[nonnegativity-preserving stencil](#diffusion-as-color-inpainting) shared with the step-8\n"
"diffusion (all eight neighbour weights $\\geq 0$), so the steered fill remains a convex\n"
"combination of its anchors : the maximum principle survives the steering. A $10^{-4}$ weight\n"
"floor keeps every cell connected where the tensor collapses to near-zero ; four orders of\n"
"magnitude under the working weights, it never competes with the steering. Pixels with\n"
"a single surviving guide get the same treatment with a one-guide fit.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1068
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"One ordering subtlety completes the step. The *deepest* channel — the one with the most clipped\n"
"photosites, whose zone contains the cores where several channels are blown at once — is not\n"
"evaluated right away : its diffused coefficients are stashed, and the evaluation runs last, after\n"
"the other clipped channels have been reconstructed, so every guide it reads is a continuous\n"
"surface. Evaluating it against a guide that jumps from measured values to a clip plateau would\n"
"print that guide's own clip contour into the result as a visible arc. Deep inside the core, where\n"
"those guides are themselves reconstructions (so each hop compounds error), the estimate blends\n"
"back toward the direct one-guide fit through a smooth weight — smooth weight times smooth fields\n"
"leaves no level set to print.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1071
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The fit quality $R^2$ is diffused alongside $(a, b, d)$ as a fourth plane, on the broader\n"
"mass-only anchor set (it stays bounded even where the fit does not).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1081
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**4. Hybrid Laplacian-band guiding of the high frequencies.** The full-signal fit transfers the\n"
"guides' fine texture with the gains implied by the total covariance ; where the colour-line is\n"
"weak that texture does not belong on the reconstructed channel. The estimate is split at\n"
"$\\sigma/4$ and its detail band is rebuilt from **two candidate sources** : the damped transfer\n"
"(the full-signal high frequencies scaled by the diffused $R^2$) and a **dedicated detail-band\n"
"colour-line** (the 2021 method's namesake, returned), fit on the high-frequency planes with\n"
"$R^2$-shrunk gains (on a\n"
"zero-mean band, shrinkage is the correct estimator : there is no magnitude to lose, only noise\n"
"to not print). The two are blended by **quadratic min-energy odds**,\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1082
#, no-wrap
msgid "w = \\frac{e_d^2}{e_d^2 + e_g^2}, \\qquad e_{d,g} = \\text{blurred } |\\text{HF}_{d,g}|,\n"
msgstr "w = \\frac{e_d^2}{e_d^2 + e_g^2}, \\qquad e_{d,g} = \\text{blurred } |\\text{HF}_{d,g}|,\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1094
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"which needs no content discriminator : a mixed-window gain misfiring at an object edge shows up\n"
"as a local spike of high-frequency energy, so the failure detects itself and the damped path\n"
"takes over exactly there.\n"
"This is what removes the last residual of the rolloff scene (its excess-edge score falls from\n"
"1.48 to 0.94 against a ground-truth floor of 0.69 : the decompressed band noise no longer\n"
"prints — the rim-bias fixes of the final build bring it to 0.74, and the band override of\n"
"step 2 to 0.64, the results table) while\n"
"*improving* the textured cases the pure detail-band fit used to break.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1101
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**5. Soft saturation floor.** The physical floor (a clipped channel is at least its saturated\n"
"reading $c_0$) is applied as a rounded constraint,\n"
"$\\tfrac{1}{2}\\big(e + c_0 + \\sqrt{(e - c_0)^2 + (0.02\\\\,c_0)^2}\\\\,\\big)$ : the hard\n"
"$\\max(e, c_0)$ prints the binding contour as an edge wherever a weak prediction oscillates\n"
"around saturation. The $0.02\\\\,c_0$ transition width is two percent of the saturated value —\n"
"below anything visible, but wide enough that the constraint's gradient never jumps.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1108
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**6. Depth-gated, hue-coupled self-dome.** Where the model is doubtful *and* the pixel is\n"
"shallow, a smooth self-continuation takes over, built **hue-coupled** (the channels are coupled\n"
"through one shared chrominance, so the perceived hue cannot drift) : one shared biharmonic\n"
"luminance dome times a harmonically-filled chrominance, never three independent channels, so the\n"
"fallback cannot split the hue toward green/magenta (the failure that kept its per-channel ancestor\n"
"disabled). The hand-over weight is :\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1109
#, no-wrap
msgid "\\text{dome fraction} = \\big(1 - S_{0.4}^{0.85}(R^2)\\big)\\; e^{-\\left(\\delta / 1.5\\sigma\\right)^2}\n"
msgstr "\\text{dome fraction} = \\big(1 - S_{0.4}^{0.85}(R^2)\\big)\\; e^{-\\left(\\delta / 1.5\\sigma\\right)^2}\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1124
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"where $\\delta$ is the pixel's depth inside the clipped zone (its distance to the nearest\n"
"valid pixel), $\\sigma$ the fitting scale, and $S$ a smoothstep, a soft ramp from 0 to 1\n"
"between the two thresholds, here mapping fit quality below $0.4$ to \"doubtful\" and above $0.85$\n"
"to \"trusted\". The band edges and the $1.5\\sigma$ depth scale were tuned on the ground-truth\n"
"bench ; the depth scale ties the dome's reach to the fitting window's own reach, so the hand-over\n"
"happens where the fit genuinely runs out of samples. The two factors answer two different questions : $R^2$ asks *is the\n"
"colour-line real here*, and depth asks *is the dome trustworthy here* (biharmonic extrapolation\n"
"is excellent near the rim and degrades with distance). Depth is the only signal we found whose\n"
"distributions actually separate correlated deep zones from decorrelated shallow content\n"
"(see [the graveyard](#annex--the-graveyard)) ; deep interiors always\n"
"stay on the coefficient field.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1131
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**7. Joint core, feathered.** All-clipped pixels have no guides : the shared biharmonic\n"
"luminance dome and the screened rim-chrominance diffusion of the rebuild reconstruct them, unchanged —\n"
"but the composite is now **feathered** over a blurred all-clip mask instead of written through a\n"
"hard one. The dome and the diffused chrominance are both valid past the hole boundary, so blending\n"
"them into the clipped channels of the surrounding ring is continuous in space at no cost to the\n"
"core itself.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1141
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**8. Chrominance coherence.** The structure-steered chrominance of the all-clip core is now\n"
"solved *directly*. The unknown $u$ is each chrominance plane in turn ; the equation is\n"
"$\\mathrm{div}(D\\\\,\\nabla u) = 0$, the steady state of\n"
"[the anisotropic diffusion of the theory section](#diffusion-as-color-inpainting) and,\n"
"equivalently, the exact minimizer of its weighted smoothness energy\n"
"$\\int \\nabla u^\\top D\\\\,\\nabla u$, with the coefficient-field results as Dirichlet anchors,\n"
"fixed boundary values the solve must honour. The tensor is built from the **recovered\n"
"luminance** (the reconstruction's own output, smoothed by two box-blur passes) : with $g$ the\n"
"unit gradient of that smoothed luminance and $t = g^\\perp$ the isophote direction,\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1142
#, no-wrap
msgid "D = t\\,t^\\top + e^{\\,-\\lVert \\nabla L_\\text{sum} \\rVert / (4\\,\\langle \\lVert \\nabla L_\\text{sum} \\rVert \\rangle)}\\; g\\,g^\\top\n"
msgstr "D = t\\,t^\\top + e^{\\,-\\lVert \\nabla L_\\text{sum} \\rVert / (4\\,\\langle \\lVert \\nabla L_\\text{sum} \\rVert \\rangle)}\\; g\\,g^\\top\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1158
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"that is : conductance one along isophotes, exponentially damped across them, the damping\n"
"normalized by the image's own mean gradient magnitude\n"
"$\\langle \\lVert \\nabla L_\\text{sum} \\rVert \\rangle$ so the steering does not depend on exposure\n"
"(this tensor reads the recovered *summed* luminance — the coefficient fill's twin form reads\n"
"$L_\\text{mean}$). The\n"
"discretization is Weickert's nonnegativity-preserving stencil, a symmetric positive-definite\n"
"M-matrix, so the discrete *maximum principle* holds by construction : the diffused ratios can\n"
"never overshoot the rim chrominance, which the earlier explicit flow could. The sparse Cholesky\n"
"factors the core once and back-substitutes the three channels. (A solver bake-off sits behind\n"
"this choice : see [the graveyard](#annex--the-graveyard) for the\n"
"instructive failure of the *other* exact formulation.) The final remosaic composes the output\n"
"from the knee-corrected CFA, so the debiased band reaches the file, not only the fits.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1171
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[The optimization problem](#the-optimization-problem-1) states what the reconstruction\n"
"minimizes and [the algorithm](#the-algorithm-1) narrates its stages ; the\n"
"[discussion](#discussion) below analyses the design — what the parameters represent, how they\n"
"were tuned, how the choices relate to established theory. What an implementer starting from\n"
"scratch needs are the actual **signal updates** : which equation writes which plane, in which\n"
"order. Here is the complete catalogue, in execution order, for one region. Planes : per-channel estimates $u_c$ (initialized\n"
"to the bilinear interpolation of the measured mosaic, knee-corrected), binary validities $v_c$,\n"
"per-pixel floors $c_{0,c}$ (the knee-corrected measurement of every reconstructable pixel),\n"
"summed luminance $L_\\text{sum} = \\sum_c u_c$ and ratios $r_c = u_c / L_\\text{sum}$ (the steering plane\n"
"$L_\\text{mean}$ of rule 1 is the *valid-channel mean*, a separate quantity).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1175
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**1. Fit and transport the colour-line** (steps 2–3 of the algorithm). The fit is on the\n"
"**full pixel values** — never the mean-subtracted detail — and uses **only the samples where\n"
"the involved channels are valid**. In the one-guide form, over the Gaussian window $\\omega$ :\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1176
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"a_c = \\frac{\\operatorname{cov}_\\omega(u_g, u_c)}{\\operatorname{var}_\\omega(u_g) + \\varepsilon},\n"
"\\qquad\n"
"b_c = \\bar u_{c,\\omega} - a_c\\, \\bar u_{g,\\omega},\n"
"\\qquad\n"
"R^2 = \\frac{\\operatorname{cov}_\\omega(u_g, u_c)^2}{\\operatorname{var}_\\omega(u_g)\\,\\operatorname{var}_\\omega(u_c)},\n"
msgstr ""
"a_c = \\frac{\\operatorname{cov}_\\omega(u_g, u_c)}{\\operatorname{var}_\\omega(u_g) + \\varepsilon},\n"
"\\qquad\n"
"b_c = \\bar u_{c,\\omega} - a_c\\, \\bar u_{g,\\omega},\n"
"\\qquad\n"
"R^2 = \\frac{\\operatorname{cov}_\\omega(u_g, u_c)^2}{\\operatorname{var}_\\omega(u_g)\\,\\operatorname{var}_\\omega(u_c)},\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1198
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"with $\\varepsilon$ a relative\n"
"Tikhonov damping guarding the division where the guide is flat ; the two-guide form solves the\n"
"analogous $2\\times2$ normal equations for $(a, b, d)$ from the ten Gaussian-blurred moment\n"
"planes. The slope is *not* sign-clamped (an early ladder revision clamped it ; the shipped fits\n"
"are guarded instead by the anchor gates $R^2 > 0.25$ and $|a| < 64$). Two more gates an\n"
"implementer must not skip : the fit windows are weighted by a soft luminance affinity\n"
"$\\min(L_\\text{sum} / 0.35\\\\,\\bar L_\\text{sum}^{\\\\,\\text{rim}}, 1)^2$ — samples much darker than the rim (occluders)\n"
"barely vote — and a window only anchors the transport where its weighted mass exceeds both an\n"
"absolute floor (0.05) and a quarter of its unweighted valid mass, so occluded windows defer to\n"
"the fill rather than fit the occluder. Because the fit is on values, the intercept carries the **local average** of the\n"
"colour : the prediction inherits the *level* of the surrounding valid data, not just its\n"
"texture, so where the guide keeps rising into the highlight the estimate follows it — *above*\n"
"the clip value. In practice the fit is never run per pixel : the moments are Gaussian-blurred\n"
"product planes, centered on the per-region valid means against float cancellation.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1205
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"{{< note >}}\n"
"Fitting from the **valid samples only** is essential. The clipped samples are pinned at the\n"
"white point ; including them would flatten the observed slope, and the model would reproduce\n"
"the clipped value instead of extrapolating past it. This is the single subtlety that separates\n"
"a working reconstruction from one that merely re-paints the clip.\n"
"{{< /note >}}\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1209
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Gate the anchors ($R^2 > 0.25$, bounded slopes, trusted mass), then diffuse each\n"
"coefficient plane by anchored Jacobi sweeps on the coarse grid — the update of one sweep at a\n"
"non-anchor cell $i$, with the eight Weickert weights $w_{ik}$ of the tensor $D$ :\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1210
#, no-wrap
msgid "a_i \\;\\leftarrow\\; \\frac{\\sum_{k \\in \\mathcal{N}_8(i)} w_{ik}\\, a_k}{\\sum_{k \\in \\mathcal{N}_8(i)} w_{ik}},\n"
msgstr "a_i \\;\\leftarrow\\; \\frac{\\sum_{k \\in \\mathcal{N}_8(i)} w_{ik}\\, a_k}{\\sum_{k \\in \\mathcal{N}_8(i)} w_{ik}},\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1218
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"anchors held fixed, 100 sweeps per pyramid level, coarsest level seeded with the anchor mean and\n"
"each finer level seeded by bilinear upsampling of the coarser solution ; same update for $b$, $d$\n"
"and $R^2$. Then **evaluate** the transported model against the measured guides, at every pixel\n"
"where the target is clipped and both guides are valid :\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1219
#, no-wrap
msgid "u_c(x) \\;\\leftarrow\\; a(x)\\, u_{g_1}(x) + b(x)\\, u_{g_2}(x) + d(x).\n"
msgstr "u_c(x) \\;\\leftarrow\\; a(x)\\, u_{g_1}(x) + b(x)\\, u_{g_2}(x) + d(x).\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1226
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Pixels with a single valid guide take the same update from the one-guide fit\n"
"$u_c \\leftarrow a\\\\, u_g + d$. The deepest channel's evaluation is deferred until the other\n"
"clipped channels are rebuilt, so its guides are continuous surfaces.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1234
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**2. Rebuild the high frequencies** (step 4). Split $u_{g}$ into low frequency\n"
"$\\bar u_g$ (Gaussian at $\\sigma/4$, floored at 2 px — the *moments* use the fit's $\\sigma$,\n"
"the band split does not) and detail $u_g - \\bar u_g$ ; form the two\n"
"candidates — the guide transfer $h_g = a\\\\,(u_{g_1} - \\bar u_{g_1}) + b\\\\,(u_{g_2} - \\bar u_{g_2})$\n"
"and the damped self-detail $h_d = R^2 (u_c - \\bar u_c)$ — and blend them by quadratic\n"
"min-energy odds on their local (Gaussian-blurred) energies $e_g, e_d$, exactly as step 4\n"
"states (a hard switch would reintroduce a hand-off seam) :\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1235
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"u_c \\;\\leftarrow\\; \\bar u_c + w\\, h_g + (1 - w)\\, h_d,\n"
"\\qquad\n"
"w = \\frac{e_d^2}{e_d^2 + e_g^2}.\n"
msgstr ""
"u_c \\;\\leftarrow\\; \\bar u_c + w\\, h_g + (1 - w)\\, h_d,\n"
"\\qquad\n"
"w = \\frac{e_d^2}{e_d^2 + e_g^2}.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1243
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**3. Soft saturation floor** (step 5), everywhere a channel is reconstructable, with\n"
"$w = 0.02\\\\, c_{0,c}$ :\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1244
#, no-wrap
msgid "u_c \\;\\leftarrow\\; c_{0,c} + \\tfrac{1}{2}\\left( (u_c - c_{0,c}) + \\sqrt{(u_c - c_{0,c})^2 + w^2}\\right).\n"
msgstr "u_c \\;\\leftarrow\\; c_{0,c} + \\tfrac{1}{2}\\left( (u_c - c_{0,c}) + \\sqrt{(u_c - c_{0,c})^2 + w^2}\\right).\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1253
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**4. Depth-gated self-dome** (step 6). Solve one shared biharmonic continuation of the\n"
"luminance over the hole, $\\Delta^2 L_b = 0$ with $L_b$ anchored on the rim (direct sparse\n"
"Cholesky on the 13-point discrete bilaplacian, coarse grid — the same solver the\n"
"implementation section documents), split its chrominance from the rim\n"
"($\\bar r_c$, harmonic fill), and blend by the dome fraction $f$ :\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1254
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"u_c \\;\\leftarrow\\; (1 - f)\\, u_c + f\\, L_b\\, \\bar r_c,\n"
"\\qquad\n"
"f = \\big(1 - S_{0.4}^{0.85}(R^2)\\big)\\, e^{-(\\delta / 1.5\\sigma)^2},\n"
msgstr ""
"u_c \\;\\leftarrow\\; (1 - f)\\, u_c + f\\, L_b\\, \\bar r_c,\n"
"\\qquad\n"
"f = \\big(1 - S_{0.4}^{0.85}(R^2)\\big)\\, e^{-(\\delta / 1.5\\sigma)^2},\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1262
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"with $\\delta$ the pixel's **depth** inside the clipped zone (its distance to the nearest valid\n"
"pixel — the only meaning $\\delta$ carries in this article).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1271
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**5. All-clipped core** (steps 7–8), on pixels where no channel survived. Magnitude : the\n"
"biharmonic dome $\\Delta^2 L = 0$ anchored on the (already reconstructed) annulus. Chrominance :\n"
"first the screened-Poisson rim fill per channel, $(\\Delta - \\lambda)\\\\, r_c = -\\lambda\\\\, \\bar c_c$\n"
"with $\\bar c_c$ the mean valid chromaticity of the padded region and $\\lambda$ the flat-colour\n"
"reaction (direct sparse solve, shared factorization) ; then the structure-steered pass. Its\n"
"primary form is the **divergence-form exact solve** of step 8 (edge-weighted 8-neighbour\n"
"graph Laplacian, direct sparse factorization) ; cores above $2^{14}$ unknowns take the\n"
"explicit trace-form pyramid instead — steps under the obstacle, iterated 240 times per level :\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1272
#, no-wrap
msgid "r_c \\;\\leftarrow\\; \\max\\!\\Big( r_c + 0.18 \\,\\big( D_{xx} \\partial_{xx} r_c + 2 D_{xy} \\partial_{xy} r_c + D_{yy} \\partial_{yy} r_c \\big),\\; \\frac{c_{0,c}}{L_\\text{sum}} \\Big),\n"
msgstr "r_c \\;\\leftarrow\\; \\max\\!\\Big( r_c + 0.18 \\,\\big( D_{xx} \\partial_{xx} r_c + 2 D_{xy} \\partial_{xy} r_c + D_{yy} \\partial_{yy} r_c \\big),\\; \\frac{c_{0,c}}{L_\\text{sum}} \\Big),\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1280
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"followed by a 60-sweep projected polish at full resolution (activity-gated : it runs only\n"
"where some pixel actually sits on its floor). Reassembly, per pixel of the all-clip core —\n"
"the only pixels this pass writes ; partial-clip pixels were settled by rules 1–4 and act as\n"
"its anchors :\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1281
#, no-wrap
msgid "u_c \\;\\leftarrow\\; L_\\text{sum}\\, \\frac{r_c}{\\sum_j r_j},\n"
msgstr "u_c \\;\\leftarrow\\; L_\\text{sum}\\, \\frac{r_c}{\\sum_j r_j},\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1288
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"soft-floored as in rule 3. (The code also carries a magnitude-transfer branch for\n"
"partially-valid pixels, a ladder-era leftover that the anchor construction makes\n"
"unreachable — documented here so nobody transcribes it.)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1292
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**6. Grain and composite.** Add the Poissonian grain of the next subsection where requested,\n"
"then write back through the hard switch : reconstructable photosites take\n"
"$\\max(\\text{raw}, u_c)$, valid photosites keep their measurement untouched.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1295
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Everything else in the pipeline — the knee estimation, the segmentation, the padding — prepares\n"
"inputs for these six updates ; nothing else writes a pixel.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1296
#, no-wrap
msgid "Discussion"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1302
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The operators the algorithm composes are not arbitrary : each is the estimator its energy term\n"
"prescribes, and each carries measurable properties that the design leans on. This subsection\n"
"derives them, and closes with the parameter study that sizes the whole method — how far a\n"
"reconstruction should reach.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ####
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1303
#, no-wrap
msgid "Trusting the guide"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1312
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The colour-line borrow is only as good as the assumption behind it : that the clipped channel\n"
"and its guide are, locally, affinely related. On a natural surface they are ; on pathological\n"
"content (independent per-channel gradients, or a boundary between two differently-coloured\n"
"materials) they are not, and forcing the borrow would paint in structure that does not belong.\n"
"The fit itself reports how far to trust it : $R^2$ (defined with the fit, in\n"
"[the update rules](#the-update-rules-1)) is the share of the channel's local variance the\n"
"colour-line explains — $1$ where the model holds, $0$ where the borrow is meaningless.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1330
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"So the method never *switches* between cross-channel and single-channel filling — it **blends\n"
"them by confidence**, falling back to extending the clipped channel's *own* gradient inward\n"
"(per-channel [biharmonic inpainting](#biharmonic-inpainting), anchored on that channel's true\n"
"valid rim) as the colour-line weakens. The blend weight is the **squared** confidence\n"
"$W_e = (R^2)^2$, and the exponent is a measured choice, not taste. Over the clipped pixels,\n"
"$R^2$ separates the two regimes only with a soft margin : it averages $\\approx 0.9$ on\n"
"natural-like content, $\\approx 0.65$ on decorrelated content, and the two distributions overlap\n"
"by $\\sim15\\\\%$ — and no cheaper statistic does better (cross-scale slope stability and\n"
"inter-guide agreement were both measured to separate *worse*, so $R^2$ is the honest ceiling).\n"
"Used linearly, the decorrelated case would still take $\\sim65\\\\%$ of a cross-channel estimate\n"
"that is both wrong and — because the hard guide selection flips there — *discontinuous*.\n"
"Squaring pulls the regimes apart : $0.9^2 \\approx 0.81$ barely moves the trustworthy case,\n"
"while $0.65^2 \\approx 0.42$ halves the untrustworthy one, so decorrelated pixels lean on the\n"
"**smooth** own-gradient fill. Because the margin is soft, though, a *faint* seam still survives\n"
"on the most adversarial content : squaring cannot fully hide a discontinuity in the quantity it\n"
"weights, and that residue is what the never-create-seams design rule exists for\n"
"(see [the graveyard](#annex--the-graveyard)).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1342
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Where **no** channel survives there is no guide and no $R^2$ to weigh, so the reconstruction\n"
"hands off to the joint core of the [next section](#filling-holes-with-no-survivor). The blend\n"
"is thus gated by **guide-validity** and weighted by squared correlation, not by a hard count of\n"
"clipped channels : one mechanism spans the whole range from a one-channel clip (mostly\n"
"cross-channel) through a two-channel clip (the surviving channel guides) to a fully-blown core\n"
"(the joint dome). This is what makes the method degrade gracefully as inter-channel correlation\n"
"falls : on the natural-like test images the cross-channel term dominates, on the adversarial\n"
"random gradients the self-extension takes over, and the reconstruction never fabricates a\n"
"colour-line that is not there. It is the *correlation*, not the number of survivors, that\n"
"decides whether a guide can be trusted — a two-survivor pixel on decorrelated content is no\n"
"better guided than a one-survivor pixel on a clean colour-line.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ####
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1343
#, no-wrap
msgid "Filling holes with no survivor"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1348
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Where *every* channel clips, no colour-line can be fit: the highlight's fine detail and its exact\n"
"peak are genuinely lost. But two things can still be salvaged from the surroundings, provided they\n"
"are reconstructed *jointly* : the hole's low-frequency **magnitude** curvature and its **chrominance**.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1358
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The naive move is to dome each channel independently: run the per-channel biharmonic self-inpaint of\n"
"the confidence fallback, now unweighted, on all three channels. It fails in an instructive way.\n"
"Because the channels clip at **different radii** (each has its own white level, and a near-neutral\n"
"highlight crosses them in turn), each channel is domed from a rim at a *different* distance from the\n"
"centre, and the three domes reach *different* heights. The last channel to clip saturates flat right\n"
"at its rim, so it carries almost no inward slope and its dome barely rises, while the first channel\n"
"to clip is domed across a wide radius and rises steeply. The core therefore drifts **off-hue**: a\n"
"neutral sun blown out over an orange sky reconstructs as a **yellow** disk, because blue (the last to\n"
"clip here) collapses while red over-recovers. Three correct-looking 1-D domes, one wrong colour.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1364
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The fix is to separate what is shared from what is not. **Magnitude** is common to all three channels\n"
"(they are all bright because the same light overflowed them), so it is reconstructed **once**, as a\n"
"single dome. **Chrominance** varies smoothly and is carried inward from the rim. Concretely, split the\n"
"summed luminance $L_\\text{sum} = R+G+B$ from the chrominance $\\text{RGB}/L_\\text{sum}$, reconstruct each by its proper\n"
"operator, and recombine $\\text{core}\\_c = L\\_{\\text{dome}}\\cdot (\\text{RGB}/L)\\_c$.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #####
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1365
#, no-wrap
msgid "The magnitude dome"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1382
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The luminance $L_\\text{sum}$ is domed over the all-clipped core by the [biharmonic\n"
"inpainting](#biharmonic-inpainting) introduced in first\n"
"principles : the solve $\\Delta^2 L = 0$, anchored to the **true valid rim** of the core (the\n"
"already-reconstructed partial-clip annulus that surrounds it). The operator itself is a revival :\n"
"a 2021 design had tried gradient extension as a reverse-sign Laplacian (the *diffuse or sharpen*\n"
"trick), but iterating a reverse diffusion is unstable and it was dropped as artifact-prone ; the\n"
"rebuild brings the idea back in its stable, direct form, solved *once* on the summed luminance\n"
"rather than iterated per channel. Filling the magnitude by plain\n"
"diffusion would flatten it into a matte disk; the biharmonic solve instead continues the rim's slope,\n"
"so a large all-clipped core **rises into a dome** rather than collapsing to a plateau. Because all\n"
"three channels ride on this one dome, none can collapse relative to the others — the failure above is\n"
"structurally impossible. It cannot reach the exact peak (the steepest part of the gradient was\n"
"clipped away, and the true summit is simply unobserved), but it recovers roughly $75$–$80\\\\%$ of the\n"
"clipped rise, as a smooth dome of the correct width. Solving a *single* scalar field rather than three\n"
"also makes the biharmonic system a third the size.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #####
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1383
#, no-wrap
msgid "A saturation floor"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1395
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The guided fit and the biharmonic dome are both *extrapolations*, and an extrapolation can undershoot:\n"
"a channel rebuilt from a single low survivor, or a dome continuing a rim whose inward slope was\n"
"flattened by clipping, can come out **below the level the channel actually reached**. That is\n"
"unphysical : as the [problem](#the-problem) established, the\n"
"photosite well fills to a fixed capacity, so a *clipped* channel is known to sit **at least** at its\n"
"clip level. Two floors enforce exactly that, and both are **monotone** : they only ever raise a value,\n"
"so they cannot overshoot and cannot shift a hue that was already correct (a note of attribution :\n"
"the floors, like the 9-point Laplacian, were already in the 2021 C implementation — the study's\n"
"contribution is only to have *measured* their worth, and the floors alone are a strict, uniform\n"
"improvement on every scene) :\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1399
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"* every clipped channel is floored at its own saturated reading;\n"
"* the all-clipped core's luminance dome is floored at the **sum** of the clip levels : every channel\n"
"  there is maxed, so the core is the *brightest* region, never a dip below its rim.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1403
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Cheap and physically unarguable, the floors remove the residual magenta-and-dark cast that the dome\n"
"and diffusion alone can leave in a large all-clipped core (a blown sun disc), and they account for the\n"
"improvement on the all-clipped correlated case reported below.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #####
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1404
#, no-wrap
msgid "Chrominance, by diffusion"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1414
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The chrominance $r = \\text{RGB}/L_\\text{sum}$ is diffused inward from the core rim : harmonic inpainting of the\n"
"chrominance, $\\Delta r = 0$ with $r$ fixed on the rim. Crucially the rim here is the **reconstructed annulus**\n"
"immediately around the core, not the distant sky: as the surviving channels were guided back toward\n"
"neutral approaching the highlight, the annulus is already near-neutral, so the diffused core comes out\n"
"**near-neutral too** — the blown sun is repainted white, not the sky's orange. (The earlier à-trous\n"
"implementation instead pulled its chrominance from too far out and yellowed the core; both the reference\n"
"and the current segmented reconstruction diffuse from the near annulus, as here.) The recombined\n"
"$\\text{core}\\_c = L\\_{\\text{dome}}\\cdot r\\_c$ is then a correctly-coloured dome.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1418
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The **previous** à-trous implementation realised this $\\Delta r = 0$ solve not as one linear system\n"
"but as an iterated relaxation: decomposing the ratios into wavelet bands, each detail band takes one\n"
"explicit Euler step of\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1419
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\\begin{align}\n"
"r &\\leftarrow r + \\kappa \\, \\big( \\Delta r - \\lambda \\, r \\big)\\\\\n"
"\\kappa &= \\frac{1}{\\texttt{B_SPLINE_TO_LAPLACIAN}} = \\frac{\\sigma_B^2}{2\\sqrt{\\pi}} \\approx 0.31\n"
"\\end{align}\n"
msgstr ""
"\\begin{align}\n"
"r &\\leftarrow r + \\kappa \\, \\big( \\Delta r - \\lambda \\, r \\big)\\\\\n"
"\\kappa &= \\frac{1}{\\texttt{B_SPLINE_TO_LAPLACIAN}} = \\frac{\\sigma_B^2}{2\\sqrt{\\pi}} \\approx 0.31\n"
"\\end{align}\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1432
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"with $\\Delta$ the isotropic 9-point Laplacian $\\mathbf{K}_{\\text{iso}}$. The constant $\\kappa$\n"
"rescales the à-trous detail band (a difference of B-splines) into a correctly-scaled continuous\n"
"Laplacian and sets the effective diffusion time step.[^ripl] The **rebuilt** reconstruction solves\n"
"$\\Delta r = 0$ directly instead : a sparse solve in the prototype, conjugate gradient (an\n"
"iterative solver that refines its answer step by step) in the C. But\n"
"the relaxation view still exposes two things:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1441
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"* With $\\lambda = 0$ it is the pure **heat equation** $\\partial r / \\partial t = \\kappa \\Delta r$ on the colour\n"
"  ratios : harmonic inpainting that fills the hole's chrominance smoothly from its rim, the Dirichlet\n"
"  minimizer derived above (equivalent to the direct $\\Delta r = 0$ solve, iterated).\n"
"* The term $-\\lambda\\\\, r$, controlled by the `solid_color` parameter, is a **first-order reaction**\n"
"  damping the ratio detail toward zero. Its Euler–Lagrange equation is the screened-Poisson /\n"
"  modified-Helmholtz equation $\\Delta r - \\lambda\\\\, r = 0$ : a diffusion held back by a restoring\n"
"  pull toward zero; larger $\\lambda$ pulls the interior chrominance\n"
"  toward a flatter, more uniform \"solid color\" fill.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1445
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The diffusion is purely **isotropic**: texture should follow structure, but chrominance should fill without\n"
"regard to direction, so a rotationally-symmetric smoother is what is wanted. The whole joint fill is\n"
"**gated to the all-clipped pixels**, so it never disturbs a channel the guided step already recovered.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1454
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**The saturation floors, as obstacles.** One measurement survives even where all three channels\n"
"are blown : each photosite's saturated reading is a **lower bound** on its true value, so in\n"
"ratio space the chrominance of a clipped channel can never drop below $c_{0,c} / L_\\text{sum}$. Applied\n"
"only at the very end — a hard $\\max$ at the recombination — that bound printed an exactly-flat\n"
"shelf at the clip level, ending in a gradient break, wherever the smooth fill under-predicted a\n"
"channel near its own rim (measured on a real sunset's blue channel : ten pixels flat at the\n"
"clip value, then a slope discontinuity). The shipped reconstruction instead treats the floors\n"
"as a constraint of the diffusion itself — an **obstacle problem** :\n"
msgstr ""

# TRANSLATOR Claude
#. type: Fenced code block (math)
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1455
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\\min_{r_c} \\int_{\\Omega} \\nabla r_c^{\\top} D\\, \\nabla r_c \\;\\mathrm{d}\\Omega\n"
"\\qquad \\text{subject to} \\qquad\n"
"r_c \\;\\geq\\; \\frac{c_{0,c}}{L_\\text{sum}} \\quad \\text{on the clipped pixels,}\n"
msgstr ""
"\\min_{r_c} \\int_{\\Omega} \\nabla r_c^{\\top} D\\, \\nabla r_c \\;\\mathrm{d}\\Omega\n"
"\\qquad \\text{subject to} \\qquad\n"
"r_c \\;\\geq\\; \\frac{c_{0,c}}{L_\\text{sum}} \\quad \\text{on the clipped pixels,}\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1473
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"solved by **projected relaxation** : after every smoothing step, $r_c \\leftarrow \\max(r_c,\n"
"c_{0,c}/L_\\text{sum})$. Every neighbour weight of the discretization is nonnegative, so the projected\n"
"scheme stays monotone and converges to the variational-inequality solution : the constraint's\n"
"influence spreads smoothly through the field — the fill lifts *around* the active set instead\n"
"of being clamped pointwise — and the recombination then only applies a soft rounding (the same\n"
"two-percent smooth-max as the coefficient-field floor) to a field that is already admissible.\n"
"The obstacle rides the whole coarse-to-fine ladder (per-level cell obstacles) plus a short\n"
"projected polish at full resolution, which also covers the direct-solve path — an exact sparse\n"
"factorization cannot project mid-solve. A stronger variant, raising the obstacle by the rim's\n"
"measured outward slope extrapolated inward, was implemented, measured, and **rejected** : it\n"
"fabricates structure where the extrapolation binds (the magenta sun's error rose by 14 %) and\n"
"changes nothing where the plain obstacle already holds.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1480
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"{{% figure src=\"./magenta-sun.png\" %}}\n"
"The desperate all-clipped case: a bright sun blown past every channel's (per-channel) white point,\n"
"over an orange sky. The sensor records a flat disk that white balance RGB coefficients will turn **magenta** ; the previous method returns a\n"
"dim, over-sized **yellow** disk with a hard edge (its per-channel fills drift off-hue and never dome);\n"
"the corrected method rebuilds a **neutral** dome of the right size from one shared luminance dome plus\n"
"rim-diffused chrominance. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1485
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Over the clipped core, RMSE $0.87 \\to 0.27$ and SSIM $0.61 \\to 0.95$; the fill's\n"
"chrominance moves from magenta $(0.37, 0.27, 0.36)$ to a near-neutral $(0.39, 0.33, 0.28)$, essentially the\n"
"ground truth's $(0.36, 0.33, 0.31)$ (the previous method lands at a yellow $(0.51, 0.34, 0.15)$).\n"
"{{% /figure %}}\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ####
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1486
#, no-wrap
msgid "Adding grain"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1493
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"As a final touch, and only where the mask is open, the reconstruction receives **Poissonian** noise\n"
"of amplitude proportional to the local value ($\\sigma_c = \\texttt{noise\\_level}\\cdot u_c$), folded to\n"
"be strictly brightening and composited by $\\alpha$. Photon shot noise is signal-dependent, so a\n"
"perfectly smooth patch dropped into a high-ISO frame looks plastic; matching the grain lets the\n"
"repair disappear.[^impl]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ####
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1494
#, no-wrap
msgid "The reconstruction radius"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1498
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"How wide should the coarsest guided window, the *reconstruction radius* $\\rho$, be? It is the one\n"
"knob that trades reach for locality, and it turns out to have a clean answer.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1501
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**The radius of a hole is its depth, not its size.** For a hole $\\Omega$, let $d(x)$ be the distance\n"
"from a clipped pixel $x$ to the nearest *valid* pixel. The quantity that matters is the deepest point,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1503
#, no-wrap
msgid "$$R=\\max\\_{x\\in\\Omega} d(x)=\\max\\big(\\text{distance transform of }\\Omega\\big)$$\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1508
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"not the bounding box. A compact disk and a long thin diagonal streak can share a bounding box while\n"
"having completely different $R$ : for the streak, $R$ is its half-*thickness*, because that is how far\n"
"the guide has to reach to touch valid data. Sizing the radius from the bounding box would massively\n"
"over-reach on elongated or diagonal holes.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1515
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**Why $\\rho \\approx R$ is optimal.** Two errors compete as $\\rho$ grows. *Coverage* : a window of\n"
"scale $\\rho$ puts weight $\\sim e^{-d(x)^2/2\\rho^2}$ on valid data, which is negligible until\n"
"$\\rho \\gtrsim d(x)$ ; below that the fit is undetermined and the pixel is effectively unreconstructed.\n"
"*Locality* : once covered, the fitted colour-line is a window-average of the spatially-varying true\n"
"one, so extrapolating from ever more distant samples adds a bias that grows with $\\rho$. The\n"
"per-pixel error is therefore\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1517
#, no-wrap
msgid "$$E(x;\\rho)\\approx \\underbrace{C_1\\\\,e^{-d(x)^2/2\\rho^2}}\\_{\\text{coverage}\\ \\downarrow}+\\underbrace{C_2\\\\,\\rho}\\_{\\text{locality}\\ \\uparrow}$$\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1522
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"whose minimum sits at $\\rho^\\*(x)\\approx d(x)$ : the smallest window that reaches valid data. A single\n"
"region radius must cover its deepest pixel, so $\\rho=R$; the coarse-to-fine ladder is then exactly\n"
"this per-pixel optimum made continuous : the coarsest scale $R$ serves the centre, each finer scale\n"
"serves the shell at its own depth.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1530
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**Over-reach is free in quality, but not in price.** In the prototype, sweeping $\\rho$ from $0.4R$ to\n"
"$3R$ leaves both the average and the deep-core RMSE **flat**, on correlated *and* on decorrelated\n"
"scenes alike. The reason is structural : the coarse-to-fine ladder overwrites each coarse\n"
"(over-smoothed) value with the finest scale that still reaches the pixel, so the radius sets only\n"
"*coverage*, never a pixel's final value. Compute, however, is not flat (it rises with both the\n"
"padded area and the number of scales), so the quality-per-cost ratio *falls* monotonically with\n"
"$\\rho$ :\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1539
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"{{< table caption=\"The reconstruction-radius study : error and cost against the fitting scale as a fraction of the region radius. RMSE = root-mean-square error against ground truth, 0 is a perfect reconstruction.\" >}}\n"
"| $\\rho/R$ | avg RMSE | deep-core RMSE | relative cost | quality / price |\n"
"|---:|---:|---:|---:|---:|\n"
"| 0.4 | 0.083 | 0.141 | 0.43 | **1.00** |\n"
"| 1.0 | 0.083 | 0.141 | 1.00 | 0.43 |\n"
"| 2.0 | 0.083 | 0.141 | 2.39 | 0.18 |\n"
"| 3.0 | 0.083 | 0.141 | 4.43 | 0.10 |\n"
"{{< /table >}}\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1551
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**The sweet spot is per-pixel, and the implementation delivers it.** Because quality is flat above the\n"
"depth and cost is not, the best quality/price is the *smallest* window that still covers each pixel,\n"
"i.e. $\\rho(x)=d(x)$ per pixel, never a global maximum. The ladder C realised this directly : a\n"
"merged tile took the group's largest radius $R$ as its coarsest scale (so the deepest pixel was\n"
"covered), and every pixel was then gated to scales no coarser than $\\sim2\\\\,d(x)$, so a shallow pixel\n"
"(a small hole, or the rim of a big one) never paid for the coarse scales only the centre needs. The\n"
"distance transform is computed once for the whole frame and drives the per-region radius. The only\n"
"firm rule is the asymmetry : never go *below* the depth (coverage collapses), and never far *above*\n"
"it (pure wasted compute). The [shipped method](#the-algorithm-1)\n"
"keeps the conclusion in a simpler form : one fit window sized to the region's radius,\n"
"$\\sigma = \\operatorname{clip}(r/6,\\\\, 8,\\\\, 64)$ px, with no per-pixel gating left to do.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1557
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Two implementations exist : the NumPy reference published next to this article, and the C /\n"
"OpenCL production code that ships in Ansel. They are diffed against each other as part of the\n"
"validation protocol, and they drift only where speed demands it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ####
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1558
#, no-wrap
msgid "The C production code"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1572
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The prototype accompanying this article is the *reference* : it favours clarity and accuracy over\n"
"speed (full-image sparse-direct solves, a fixed Gaussian ladder, a separate variance pass, one\n"
"colour-line fit per (channel, guide) pair). The code that actually ships in Ansel has to reconstruct\n"
"a clipped sun inside a 20+ Mpx raw while the user waits, so it drifts from the reference in a handful\n"
"of deliberate ways. Every trade-off below is tuned for **correlated content, the overwhelmingly\n"
"common case in natural images**, and accepts a small loss on synthetic *decorrelated* content, which\n"
"is rare in practice. Each deviation is reversible in the source. A note on history : this\n"
"optimization work was done on the ladder-era C, whose reconstruction core the shipped method\n"
"[replaces](#the-algorithm-1). The segmentation, padding, sparse\n"
"solver and shared-statistics machinery carry over verbatim ; the ladder-specific items (the\n"
"per-hole scale ladder, the per-pixel depth gate, the pair-restricted guide choice) survive only\n"
"as principles, inside the single fit window and the coefficient fill of the shipped method.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1579
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"* **Segment and reconstruct only the clipped neighbourhoods, at full resolution.** The reference\n"
"  runs on the whole frame. The shipped code flood-fills the clipped mask into connected regions,\n"
"  pads each by its own reconstruction radius ($1.25\\times$ the radius, clamped between $8$ and\n"
"  $256$ px — the larger the hole, the farther it must reach for valid data), merges regions whose padded boxes overlap so their fills never meet as a seam, and\n"
"  runs the full pipeline only inside each padded box. *Cost :* none — the untouched pixels were\n"
"  already correct. *Win :* the work scales with the clipped area, not with the sensor.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1599
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"* **A standalone sparse Cholesky closed the solver gap.** The reference fills the magnitude dome\n"
"  with a sparse direct solve (`scipy.spsolve`); an iterative solver (conjugate gradient on\n"
"  $\\Delta^2$) stalls in single precision at raw scale (its condition number, the factor by which\n"
"  the system amplifies rounding errors, grows like the fourth\n"
"  power of the region size), and a dense factorisation is $O(N^3)$, so the C first shipped a dense\n"
"  Cholesky (the standard exact factorisation of a symmetric system into triangular halves,\n"
"  computed once and reused) on a grid coarsened to at most 2000 unknowns. The dome being low-frequency, the coarse\n"
"  solve was exact *where it mattered* — except on huge fully-blown cores, where the coarsening\n"
"  itself became the accuracy bottleneck (the magenta-sun test case improved by 21 % in RMSE the day\n"
"  the cap was lifted). The C now carries its own sparse symmetric-positive-definite (SPD) Cholesky, an up-looking $LL^T$\n"
"  factorisation in double precision, ordered by *geometric nested dissection* : the unknowns are 2D\n"
"  grid points, so recursive coordinate bisection delivers the fill-reducing quality that normally\n"
"  requires an approximate-minimum-degree (AMD) implementation, in a few dozen lines and with no\n"
"  external dependency. The dome\n"
"  grid is four times finer (8 192 unknowns, which measurably saturates the quality gain), and the\n"
"  all-clip core's chrominance diffusion factors once for its three channel right-hand sides when the\n"
"  core is small ; the parallel conjugate gradient measurably beats the serial factorisation on the\n"
"  big ones, so it keeps them. *Cost :* none net (the all-clip solves got faster). *Win :* the last\n"
"  systematic C-vs-prototype divergence gone, and the huge-core accuracy with it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1604
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"* **A per-hole Gaussian ladder sized to the reconstruction radius.** The reference uses a fixed\n"
"  radius ladder ($40, 24, \\dots, 2$ px). The optimized ladder C sized each region's coarsest scale to\n"
"  that region's *reconstruction radius* and halved by $2\\times$ down to $\\sim2$ px. This deserves its own\n"
"  treatment : see [The reconstruction radius](#the-reconstruction-radius) below.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1609
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"* **Shared windowed statistics : a free speed-up.** The colour-line fit needs, per channel pair, the\n"
"  windowed means, variances and covariance. Gathering them per (channel, guide) costs twelve blurs\n"
"  per scale ; gathering them per channel *pair* yields *both* channels' fits from the same two blurs :\n"
"  six blurs, and **mathematically identical**. This alone roughly halved the runtime.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1618
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"* **Pair-restricted variance for guide selection : a small, contained cost.** The reference decides\n"
"  which of two guides to trust from each guide's *single-channel* windowed variance, a separate\n"
"  three-blur pass per scale. The optimized ladder C reused the *pair-restricted* variance it already\n"
"  computed for the fit and dropped that pass entirely (nine blurs per scale down to six). This changed\n"
"  only *which* guide wins, and only where the two disagree, i.e. decorrelated content. *Cost :* on a\n"
"  fully-decorrelated synthetic scene, single-clip RMSE rises from $0.043$ to $0.047$ and SSIM falls\n"
"  from $0.964$ to $0.960$ ; on correlated scenes, and on two- or three-channel clipping, it is within\n"
"  noise. *Win :* a third of the remaining blurs removed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1631
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"* **The per-channel self-dome and seam regularizer are disabled in the shipped code.** Both smooth\n"
"  each RGB channel *independently*. On a real saturated amber/orange highlight (where the colour-line\n"
"  $R^2$ dips from clip non-linearity and is misread as \"decorrelated\") that drifts green off red and\n"
"  blue and turns the reconstruction magenta. The reference keeps them : they de-artifact genuinely\n"
"  decorrelated content, which the synthetic scenes exercise heavily and real photographs rarely do\n"
"  (disabling them costs the reference $\\sim0.01$–$0.02$ RMSE on the random scene, essentially nothing\n"
"  on correlated content). The clean fix is a *hue-coupled* version (smoothing luminance and a\n"
"  shared chrominance instead of three independent channels), and it has since been built : in the\n"
"  final [coefficient-field pipeline](#the-algorithm-1) the self-dome returns\n"
"  as the depth-gated fallback, hue-coupled exactly this way (one shared biharmonic luminance dome\n"
"  times a harmonically-filled chrominance), so the fallback cannot drift the hue by construction.\n"
"  The seam regularizer is retired for good — that pipeline has no estimator hand-offs left to iron.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1640
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Two components of the 2021 C implementation that the prototype translation had silently dropped\n"
"were **merged back into the reference**, as genuine method requirements rather than speed\n"
"trades, so they are no longer differences : the\n"
"**rotation-invariant 9-point Laplacian** (the operator this article derives ; the reference used the\n"
"plain 5-point cross before[^oono][^patra][^ripl]) and the **saturation floors**\n"
"([below](#filling-holes-with-no-survivor)). Both *improve* the hardest, most relevant case (the\n"
"all-clipped core of a correlated scene), lowering its RMSE from $0.065$ to $0.062$ and raising SSIM\n"
"from $0.959$ to $0.964$, and are neutral elsewhere.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1646
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Taken together, on a clipped sun the guided-filter blur count drops from fifteen to six per scale and\n"
"the preview reconstruction falls from tens of seconds to a few. The differences that remain are\n"
"speed and architecture (segmentation, dense solvers, the per-hole radius, shared statistics), plus\n"
"the pair-restricted guide variance and the disabled per-channel refinement above ; the core\n"
"reconstruction mathematics is shared with the reference.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1653
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"One further measured trade closed early : the reconstruction is markedly better run at **full\n"
"resolution**. The 2021 module solved on a quarter-resolution copy for speed, but that\n"
"downsampling blurs the reconstruction and, blended back against the sharp original, is the dominant\n"
"source of edge error : running full-res lowered boundary RMSE by about 30%, so the rebuild works at\n"
"full resolution. Downsampling is a\n"
"speed/quality trade, not a free lunch.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ####
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1654
#, no-wrap
msgid "The Python reference"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1660
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The NumPy mirror (`validate.py`, `fix_prototype.py`) implements every stage of the shipped\n"
"algorithm in the same order, and diffing its output against the C exports is part of the\n"
"validation protocol. A few components are deliberately *better* in Python than in C, or the C\n"
"deliberately trades exactness for speed :\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1699
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"* **Exact sparse direct solves.** The prototype's biharmonic domes and its divergence-form\n"
"  chrominance solve are `scipy.sparse` factorisations, exact to machine precision (its\n"
"  screened-Poisson *joint-core* fill, however, is a fixed 400-sweep Jacobi relaxation — on\n"
"  that one stage the C's direct factorization is the more exact of the two). The C now\n"
"  carries its own sparse Cholesky (see *Implementation & optimizations* above) and matches\n"
"  the prototype's dome and small-core chrominance\n"
"  solves ; what still differs is deliberate : the chrominance diffusion of *large* all-clip cores runs\n"
"  the parallel conjugate gradient (measured faster than a serial factorisation there, with no\n"
"  measurable quality difference), the coefficient fill stays the coarse-to-fine Jacobi\n"
"  described above — with the C's adaptive pyramid (base pitch $\\sigma/4$ capped at 8 px,\n"
"  halved to an $\\le 8$-cell coarsest, 100 sweeps per level) against the prototype's fixed\n"
"  seven full-resolution levels — and the prototype's fill is **isotropic** — the C's\n"
"  variance-adaptive\n"
"  steering of the coefficient transport ([step 3](#the-algorithm-1))\n"
"  has no Python mirror yet, so the C-vs-prototype agreement is checked with the steering's\n"
"  contribution in mind. Benefit of the prototype's exact solves : they are the arbiter when C output\n"
"  looks wrong.\n"
"* **FFT Gaussian windows vs. recursive IIR.** The prototype computes windowed moments with\n"
"  fast-Fourier-transform (FFT) convolutions : exact, deterministic. The C uses the recursive\n"
"  (infinite-impulse-response, IIR) Gaussian whose cost is\n"
"  independent of $\\sigma$ — but whose parallel implementation is *not run-to-run deterministic* :\n"
"  block-boundary rounding jitters at the last float digit, which is harmless per se but seeded a\n"
"  memorable heisenbug (below).\n"
"* **Knee estimation input.** The prototype estimates the rolloff from the full-resolution true\n"
"  RGB scene ; the C from the quad-binned CFA at $\\le 1.5$ Mpx. Measured cost : none (the blind\n"
"  C estimate still matches the analytic knee to $10^{-3}$), while the quad binning is what makes\n"
"  CFA-side estimation possible at all.\n"
"* **Full-frame vs. per-region.** The mirror processes whole frames ; the C gathers each clipped\n"
"  region into a padded buffer and reconstructs it independently, which bounds memory and lets\n"
"  regions parallelize, at the price of per-region normalization.\n"
"* **Shipped refinements the mirror has not caught up with.** Three late C rounds have no\n"
"  Python counterpart yet : the **obstacle machinery** (per-level projected relaxation, the\n"
"  full-resolution polish, and the soft reassembly floor — the mirror still applies the retired\n"
"  hard $\\max(u, c_0)$ at reassembly), the **band override** of the detection threshold for\n"
"  knee-engaged channels (worth $5\\times$ on the rolloff scene, so Py-vs-C is structurally\n"
"  incomparable there), and the C's strictly per-pixel binary validity (the mirror derives its\n"
"  mask through a 5×5 majority vote, a $\\sim 2$ px geometric dilation). These are the known\n"
"  content gaps behind the largest per-scene drifts.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1709
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"After every stage was mirrored, the residual disagreement between the C production code and\n"
"the Python reference (measured as the root-mean-square difference of their output images inside\n"
"the clipped zones) is $0.009$–$0.089$ across the bench. Its floor is the one input difference\n"
"that cannot be removed — Python fits on the true RGB scene, while the C fits on the same scene\n"
"seen through the sensor mosaic and a bilinear interpolation (about $0.02$ apart inside the\n"
"near-clip band) — and its ceiling is the shipped-refinement list above, which dominates on the\n"
"rolloff and occlusion scenes. Away from those two scenes, the implementations agree to well\n"
"within the error either makes against the ground truth ; on them, the C's extra machinery is\n"
"precisely what the drift measures.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ####
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1710
#, no-wrap
msgid "User parameters"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1720
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"There is deliberately almost nothing to set : the algorithm is **self-configuring**. Every\n"
"quantity the reconstruction depends on is either derived once and frozen, or measured from the\n"
"image itself at run time — the fitting scale from each region's own reconstruction radius, the\n"
"sensor rolloff from the image's own colour-lines, anchor trust from the measured fit quality,\n"
"the transport steering from the measured guide structure, the edge threshold $k$ calibrated\n"
"once on the ground-truth bench. The `iterations` and `diameter` controls of the 2021 mode are\n"
"gone from this mode's interface : there is no user-tunable convergence left to misconfigure,\n"
"and no way to trade quality away by accident.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1727
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"What remains is one safety and two tastes. The `clipping threshold` scales the saturation\n"
"thresholds that define the zone (see the visualization toggle below — it almost never needs\n"
"moving) ; the `noise level` sets the grain re-injected over the reconstruction so it matches\n"
"the surrounding photon texture ; and `inpaint a flat color` sets the pull toward a uniform\n"
"colour in the all-clipped cores where nothing survived — a stylistic choice about zones that\n"
"carry no information at all.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1734
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"{{< advice >}}\n"
"The clipping threshold has a mask-visualization toggle (the icon next to the slider). When active,\n"
"the module renders a **false-colour** overlay (valid pixels dimmed, clipped pixels flagged) so you\n"
"can see exactly which region $\\Omega$ the reconstruction will act on before committing to it. You\n"
"should almost never need to move the threshold itself.\n"
"{{< /advice >}}\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1743
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The method's structural limitation is inherited and accepted : a blown blue sky seen through\n"
"green leaves is recovered green, because where *no* channel survives the reconstruction can only\n"
"propagate the neighbouring colour — it was designed for the unavoidable clips around light\n"
"sources and specular reflections, whose glowing halos carry the information it feeds on. Other\n"
"situations still call for protecting the highlights at capture and raising exposure in\n"
"post-production, which modern sensors' signal-to-noise ratio comfortably allows.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1751
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Two measured caveats complete the honest picture. On the occlusion bench scene, the tuned\n"
"Darktable segmentation reaches a *higher structural-similarity* score than harmonic\n"
"transposition (0.98 against 0.96) despite values 15 % farther from the truth : magnitude and\n"
"structure are different errors, and a smooth wrong fill can look cleaner than a truthful one.\n"
"And the float pipeline's device parity is tolerance-level, not bit-level : after centering the\n"
"moment accumulation (step 3), the residual CPU-versus-GPU difference on the deepest bench scene\n"
"is below $10^{-3}$ RMSE, bounded by order-nondeterministic parallel reductions.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1752
#, no-wrap
msgid "Results"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1754
#, no-wrap
msgid "The bench"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1770
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Every number below comes from one protocol. Six synthetic scenes with known ground truth — RGB\n"
"specular balls, a magenta sun, correlated gradients (a luminance field times a smooth\n"
"chrominance, how natural images behave), independent random gradients (no colour-line at all,\n"
"the adversarial case), a PK1-like sky with an analytic sensor rolloff, and a sun crossed by an\n"
"occluder — are written as Bayer DNG files, developed by the *actual production pipelines*, and\n"
"the exports are scored against ground truth **in white-balanced sensor RGB** (a full 3×3\n"
"calibration matrix fitted on strictly-linear valid pixels maps every export back to sensor\n"
"space, so differently-matrixed pipelines land in the same units). Every Ansel result in this\n"
"section — both modes, every table, every figure — is produced by the **shipped C\n"
"implementation through `ansel-cli`**, not by the Python research prototype : the two\n"
"implementations deliberately drift (different solvers, resolutions and stage trade-offs, see\n"
"[the C production code](#the-c-production-code)), by 0.009 to 0.089 RMSE inside the clipped\n"
"zones across this bench, so their numbers must never be mixed. The whole bench reproduces\n"
"from the [annex](#annex--reproducing-the-results).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1779
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The metrics of the shipped algorithm below are computed inside the clipped area only. **RMSE** is the\n"
"root-mean-square error against the ground truth, in sensor units normalized so the clip level is\n"
"1 : it measures how far the reconstructed values are from the true ones, on average. **SSIM** is\n"
"the structural-similarity index, a perceptual score comparing local means, contrasts and\n"
"correlations (1 means visually identical). **Edge energy** is our seam detector : the\n"
"chrominance-gradient energy inside the zone, relative to a ring just outside it, and its target is\n"
"the *ground truth's own* score, not zero, because real content has texture and an over-smooth\n"
"reconstruction is as wrong as a seamy one :\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1792
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"{{< table caption=\"The shipped reconstruction against ground truth, inside the clipped zones. RMSE = root-mean-square error, 0 is a perfect reconstruction ; SSIM = structural similarity, 1 is a perfect reconstruction ; edge energy = mean gradient magnitude, best when it MATCHES the ground truth's own score (an over-smooth fill is as wrong as a seamy one). Naturals have no ground truth, so only their edge energy is shown.\" >}}\n"
"| case | RMSE | SSIM | edge energy (GT target) |\n"
"|---|---|---|---|\n"
"| RGB balls | 0.0351 | 0.995 | 0.41 (0.47) |\n"
"| magenta sun | 0.3276 | 0.952 | 0.31 (0.50) |\n"
"| correlated | 0.0398 | 0.973 | 1.15 (1.14) |\n"
"| random | 0.0453 | 0.965 | 0.85 (1.02) |\n"
"| pk1synth | 0.0053 | 1.000 | 0.64 (0.69) |\n"
"| PK1 (natural) | — | — | 0.49 |\n"
"| DSC00078 (natural) | — | — | 0.73 |\n"
"| IMG_3129 (natural) | — | — | 0.39 |\n"
"{{< /table >}}\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1794
#, no-wrap
msgid "The four methods"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1804
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The two Darktable modes are described with the other simple fixes in\n"
"[the landscape section](#simpler-fixes) ; read through this article's\n"
"framework, **inpaint opposed** is a colour-line with the *slope pinned to one* (in cube-root\n"
"space) and a single *global* intercept — where harmonic transposition fits both slope and\n"
"intercept per local window and diffuses those coefficients across the zone, opposed trusts one\n"
"fixed relationship everywhere, which is why it is nearly free and why it fails under mixed\n"
"lighting — and **segmentation based** upgrades that to one representative chrominance *per\n"
"segment*, still flat where our diffused fields vary smoothly.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1810
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Both methods answer the question \"what colour should this area be\" ; neither fits a *model* of\n"
"how the missing channel relates to the surviving ones, which is what lets our method recover\n"
"per-pixel structure and magnitude with a measured confidence. The rows below put numbers on\n"
"that difference, on the same synthetic scenes and ground truths as everything else in this\n"
"section.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1825
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Root-mean-square error (lower is better) and structural similarity (higher is better), measured\n"
"inside the clipped zone against the ground truth, after per-image exposure calibration ; every\n"
"method exported as 32-bit linear TIFF (upstream Darktable 5.x for the first two columns, Ansel\n"
"for the last two), scored by the same `validate.py` as every other table on this page. Two\n"
"precautions make the columns actually comparable. First, the **pipelines are neutralized to the\n"
"same baseline** — demosaicing plus highlight reconstruction, nothing else : both applications default\n"
"scene-referred workflow silently inserts an exposure lift, a chromatic-adaptation channel mixer\n"
"and a sigmoid tone curve around its reconstruction, which would corrupt the measurement with\n"
"rendering differences, so it is forced to `workflow=none` (Ansel's export is already that\n"
"baseline). Second, each competitor runs its **best parameters per scene**, found by a grid sweep\n"
"over its controls (clipping threshold for *opposed* ; candidating, combine, rebuild mode and\n"
"strength for *segmentation* ; iterations and flat-colour inpainting for the guided laplacians),\n"
"while harmonic transposition runs its stock defaults everywhere. Reproduce with `dt_compare.py`\n"
"(the comparison) and `tune_methods.py` (the sweep) from the research repository :\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1836
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"{{< table caption=\"The four methods against ground truth, as RMSE / SSIM per cell : RMSE = 0 is a perfect reconstruction, SSIM = 1 is a perfect reconstruction. Pipelines equalized to demosaic + highlights only, every competitor at its per-scene best parameters, all scored in white-balanced sensor RGB inside the clipped zones. Bold = best of row.\" >}}\n"
"| scene | Darktable opposed | Darktable segmentation | guided laplacians | harmonic transposition |\n"
"|---|---|---|---|---|\n"
"| `balls` (specular balls) | 0.242 / 0.814 | 0.233 / 0.831 | 0.334 / 0.744 | **0.035 / 0.995** |\n"
"| `magentasun` (magenta sun) | 0.924 / 0.707 | 0.807 / 0.767 | 0.809 / 0.678 | **0.328 / 0.952** |\n"
"| `correlated` (correlated gradients) | 0.107 / 0.872 | 0.077 / 0.907 | 0.130 / 0.850 | **0.040 / 0.973** |\n"
"| `random` (independent gradients) | 0.089 / 0.911 | 0.080 / 0.920 | 0.138 / 0.862 | **0.045 / 0.965** |\n"
"| `pk1synth` (PK1-like sky (analytic rolloff)) | 0.130 / 0.985 | 0.130 / 0.985 | 0.108 / 0.993 | **0.0053 / 1.000** |\n"
"| `occluded` (occluded sun) | 0.099 / 0.982 | 0.086 / 0.980 | 0.171 / 0.930 | **0.069 / 0.987** |\n"
"{{< /table >}}\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/resources/guided-laplacian-highlights/index.md:1847
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The pattern is consistent with the mechanisms. Even with the pipelines equalized and every\n"
"competitor at its per-scene best, harmonic transposition leads in RMSE on every scene — by\n"
"20 % where the occlusion favours the segmentation mode's assumptions, by a factor of 2 to 7 on\n"
"the general cases, by a factor of nearly 50 on the rolloff sky (where the band override below\n"
"lets the model rebuild the slope the sensor compressed away) : the Darktable modes recover a *plausible colour* but not magnitude (their fixed\n"
"unit slope cannot lift a channel above what the opposed average provides), and their per-segment\n"
"or global chrominance flattens texture. The segmentation mode does move ahead of plain opposed\n"
"once its rebuild pass is actually enabled (the sweep found *rebuild + full strength* optimal on\n"
"half the scenes). The visual counterpart of\n"
"every number, one scene per gallery, all six renditions through the same display transform :\n"
msgstr ""

